# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: river-severn
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A series of large floods occurred in parts of the United Kingdom during the summer of 2007.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] June was one of the wettest months on record in the United Kingdom (see List of weather records).
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Average rainfall across the country was 5.5 inches (140 mm); more than double the June average.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some areas received a month's worth of precipitation in 24 hours.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was the UK's wettest May–July period since records began in 1776.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] July had unusually unsettled weather and above-average rainfall through the month, peaking on 20 July as an active frontal system dumped more than 4.7 inches (120 mm) of rain in southern England.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Civil and military authorities described the June and July rescue efforts as the biggest in the UK in peacetime.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency described the July floods as critical and expected them to exceed the 1947 benchmark.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] June 2007 started quietly with an anticyclone to the north of the United Kingdom maintaining a dry, cool easterly flow.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] From 10 June the high pressure began to break down as an upper trough moved into the area, triggering thunderstorms that caused flooding in Northern Ireland on 12 June.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later that week, a slow-moving area of low pressure from the west of Biscay moved east across the British Isles.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] At the same time an associated occluded front moved into northern England, becoming very active as it did so, with the peak rainfall on 15 June.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Rainfall records were broken across the region, leading to localised flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] As it weakened, the front moved north into Scotland on 16 June and left England and Wales with a very unstable airmass, frequent heavy showers, thunderstorms and cloudy conditions.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] This led to localised flash flooding and prevented significant drying where earlier rains had fallen.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, another unseasonably low pressure (993 hPa / 29.3 inHg) depression, Cyclone Uriah, moved across England.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The associated front settled over northern and eastern England and dumped more than 3.9 inches (100 mm) of rain in places.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The combination of high rainfall and high water levels from the earlier rainfall led to extensive flooding across many parts of England and Wales, with the Midlands, Gloucestershire, Worcestershire, South, West and East Yorkshire the most affected.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Gales along the east coast also caused storm damage.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] RAF Fylingdales on the North York Moors reported rainfall totals of 4.1 inches (103 mm) in 24 hours, an estimated 3.9 inches (100 mm) in Hull and 3.0 inches (77 mm) on Emley Moor in West Yorkshire.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Until 2007, the average monthly total for June for the whole UK was 2.86 inches (72.6 mm).
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June, the Met Office released an early warning of severe weather for the approaching weekend, stating that 0.79 to 1.97 inches (20 to 50 mm) of rain could fall in some areas, raising the possibility of more flooding within the already saturated flood plains.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, another active frontal system moved across southern England.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Many places recorded a month's rainfall or more in one day.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Met Office at RAF Brize Norton in Oxfordshire reported 4.98 inches (126.6 mm): a sixth of its annual rainfall.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The college at Pershore in Worcestershire reported 5.60 inches (142.2 mm), causing the Environment Agency to issue 16 further severe flood warnings.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, many towns and villages were flooded, with Gloucestershire, Worcestershire, Warwickshire, Wiltshire, Oxfordshire, Berkshire, London and South Wales facing the brunt of the heavy rainfall.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Climate researchers suggested that the unusual weather leading to the floods might be linked to that year's appearance of La Nina in the Pacific Ocean, and to the jet stream being further south than normal.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] England was affected by the June and July floods, with the North badly hit in June, the West badly hit in July, and many areas hit in both.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was England's wettest July on record.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Gloucestershire was the worst affected county – with both some minor flooding in June, and major flooding in July.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Non-administrative counties and administrative counties affected by the flooding are given below.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 25 July, a number of low-lying parts adjacent to the river in Bedford and Luton were flooded and one man drowned attempting to swim across the River Great Ouse in Bedford.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Parts of Felmersham and Turvey were also flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, the M4 was closed after a landslide caused by flooding between Junctions 12 and 13 eastbound.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Approximately 1,100 properties in Thatcham were affected by flash flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, Newbury and Maidenhead town centres were flooded, the shopping mall in Maidenhead was closed and parts of the Glade Festival were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Officials warned that the River Thames, the River Ock, and its tributaries from Charney could burst their banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Reading, rail services to the southwest were affected, and westbound trains from Paddington could go no further.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The flood waters affected the Atomic Weapons Establishment at Burghfield, which handles the United Kingdom's nuclear warheads, resulting in a suspension of work for almost a year.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 June, Stoke Goldington suffered flash flooding affecting 25 homes.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Stoke Goldington was affected again on 3 July, with 10 houses being flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 24 July, four bridges in St Neots were shut when the river level peaked, and the Environment Agency warned residents in the St Neots, Paxton and Offords areas to expect flooding that night.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 25 July, parts of St Ives were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later the same day, the Environment Agency advised residents near the River Great Ouse that the peak had passed and further flooding was unlikely.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, heavy rainfall caused the postponement of the fourth test match between England and the West Indies at the Riverside Ground, Chester-le-Street.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 June, flash floods affected parts of Darlington and Stanhope Road, Northgate, St Cuthbert's Way, Parkgate and Haughton Road were closed after water levels rose by about 2 feet (0.6 m).
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It has also led to Woodland Road to improve its drainage to prevent such flooding on one of the main roads out the town.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, flooding affected Peterlee town centre, closing shops and a local school.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 64-year-old man hit his head and died after trying to bail out his flooded home in Alston, Cumbria.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, flooding affected properties in Coal Aston, Calow and Chesterfield town centre, and the A617 was covered by more than 2 feet (0.6 m) of floodwater causing traffic delays.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 19 July, Gloucestershire Fire and Rescue Service attended 1,800 calls in a 48-hour period, compared with the usual 8,000 calls a year.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, Gloucester City A.F.C.'s Stadium was flooded, and the Tewkesbury road at Longford was completely impassable by the Longford Inn.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Tewkesbury was completely cut off with no road access, parts of the town were under around 3 feet (0.9 m) of water and flood waters entered Tewkesbury Abbey for the first time in 247 years.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Tewkesbury's Mythe Water Treatment Works were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Severn Trent Water warned that treated water would run out by early Sunday evening in Tewkesbury, Cheltenham, Gloucester and surrounding areas.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Combined military and civil emergency services tried to prevent floods reaching the Walham electricity substation in Gloucester supplying half a million people.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 July, 50,000 Gloucestershire homes were left without electricity after a major electricity substation in Castle Meads had to be turned off.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Efforts to stop flooding at Walham substation succeeded; the Castle Meads substation was repaired the next day.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, an estimated 420,000 people were without running water, including most of the population of Gloucester, Cheltenham, and Tewkesbury.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Emergency services continued repair work at the Mythe water-treatment works, but Severn Trent Water estimated that water supplies would not be restored for at least 14 days.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 900 drinking water bowsers were brought in, and the Army was mobilised to distribute three million bottles of water a day and keep the bowsers filled.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Coors, Carlsberg, Scottish and Newcastle, Inbev and Greene King brewing companies offered 23 beer tankers to help supply drinking water.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 July, Severn Trent Water organised a temporary non-potable water supply to 10,000 homes in Tewkesbury.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was not until 7 August – 16 days after Mythe Treatment Works stopped pumping – that the tap water for the 140,000 homes affected was again declared safe to drink.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A man and his 24-year-old son died from asphyxiation from carbon monoxide poisoning on 27 July when attempting to stop flooding in the unventilated Tewkesbury Rugby Football Club cellar.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 28 July, the body of a 19-year-old man, reported missing seven days earlier, was recovered in Tewkesbury.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flooding occurred in many parts of Greater London.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Water and power supplies were not disrupted but parts of South West London were under 2 feet (61 cm) of water.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Two of four rail lines in South Croydon were closed by landslips.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The London Underground was severely disrupted and 25 stations were closed.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, Herefordshire was affected by flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The M50 motorway near Ledbury was closed on 22 July due to flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 5,200 people in and around Bromyard were without clean water on 22 and 23 July after the pumps at the Whitbourne works failed.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Once supply was restored residents were urged by Welsh Water to boil their tap-water until further notice.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The village of Hampton Bishop, 3 miles (5 km) from the city of Hereford, was surrounded and flooded by water after the River Lugg burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On the afternoon of 24 July the Fire Service began pumping flood water out of the village, but not before 130 residents were evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some houses, including the Herefordshire home of *Daily Mail* writer Quentin Letts, were flooded by a torrent of water gushing from what had previously been only a small, unnamed brook north of Ross-on-Wye.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Residents of East Bromyard were rescued after the River Frome burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Lostock Hall and Penwortham near Preston were hit by flash floods.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, heavy rain caused flooding in Earby and Ribchester, affecting homes and causing the Royal Lancashire Show to be cancelled on 9 July.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 4 July, the Blackburn Mela was cancelled due to ground conditions.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, Walton-le-Dale near Preston was hit by flash floods.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Louth and Horncastle were severely flooded, some roads in that area becoming impassable.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Children at a school in Horncastle were evacuated because of floods.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 600-flood related calls occurred across the county.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Lincoln, mainly round the Stamp End area, a house called Shuttleworth House was completely flooded with water in its insides.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] After power was lost in the area, more than 200 people were rescued in dinghies.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June 2007, flash flooding caused extensive damage to the villages of Lambley, Woodborough and Burton Joyce.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Major towns were hit including Mansfield and Hucknall but not as severely as Lambley.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The same day, flooding occurred at Retford and Worksop after the River Idle and River Ryton respectively overtopped their banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Many rivers burst their banks, including both the Thames and the Cherwell in Oxford and the Ock in Abingdon the Windrush in Witney and the Evenlode.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, Banbury and Witney were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Oxford, particularly Botley, was flooded and some 300 people were evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, the Environment Agency warned of further flooding and 1,500 people in Abingdon were evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Forty thousand sandbags were transported from Grantham in Lincolnshire to Abingdon and Oxford.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 23 July, Oxford, Abingdon, Kidlington and Bladon were affected; some 3,000 homes including the home of William Morris at Kelmscott were flooded and 600 residents were evacuated, with many taking refuge in Oxford United Football Club's Kassam Stadium.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 24 July, the Thames in Abingdon rose 3 feet (0.9 m) in less than 12 hours to a "perilously high" level and the Thames and the Severn were expected to rise to 20 feet (6.1 m) higher than normal.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 July, residents of Osney in west Oxford were advised to leave their homes.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] About 30 people went to the Kassam stadium shelter while another 250 decided to stay with family and friends.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Osney Mead substation, which supplies power to Oxford city centre, was threatened but did not flood.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later that evening the Thames breached its banks at Henley.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, rain had washed away the main road at Hampton Loade and the Severn Valley Railway line from Bridgnorth was closed after numerous landslips on the line.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Also, on 19 June/20 June, parts of the town of Shifnal near Telford were flooded when the Wesley Brook burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some of the residents blamed Severn Trent Water for opening floodgates at Priors Lee balancing lake, but no such gates existed.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Repair costs to the railway were estimated at £2 million.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, the Burway Bridge collapsed, disrupting one of the main roads into Ludlow, severing a gas main and causing the surrounding area to be evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 July, a woman was pulled out of the River Severn at Jackfield on the Telford and Wrekin border near Ironbridge.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, the UK National Ballooning Championships in Ludlow had been cancelled for the first time in their 32-year history.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, flooded parts of Warwickshire included Alcester, Stratford-upon-Avon, Shipston on Stour and Water Orton.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] To a lesser extent, areas of Leamington Spa and Warwick also experienced flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Several nature reserves in the Tame Valley, including Ladywalk and Kingsbury Water Park were badly affected, just as ground- and reedbed- nesting birds were hatching young.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 200 people were forced to leave Witton Road and Tame Road in Aston, Birmingham when the River Tame flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Water entered the streets of Shirley, Solihull.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] As in Warwickshire, the Tame caused losses at a nature reserve; this time RSPB Sandwell Valley.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In the Dudley borough, flooding damaged local schools, shops and communities.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Schools opened their doors with parts of buildings flooded with water; damage in the West Midlands area was estimated at £1.9 billion (2007 GDP).
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, Swindon had a month's rainfall in less than half a day.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 50 people were rescued from their flooded homes.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, Worcestershire was affected by flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 68-year-old motorist (Judge Eric Dickinson) died after becoming trapped in his vehicle in flood water near Pershore whilst attempting to cross an old ford in Bow Brook which was by then 2 m deep.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The waters were still rising, endangering the confluence of the River Teme and the River Severn.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June 2007 the New Road Ground, home to Worcestershire County Cricket Club, was flooded after the River Severn overtopped its banks, causing the next day's Twenty20 match against Warwickshire to be cancelled.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, Tenbury Wells in Worcestershire was flooded for the second time in three weeks after a thunderstorm caused flash flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July the M5 was affected, compounded by the closure of the Strensham services, and the motorway was closed, stranding hundreds in their vehicles overnight.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 23 July, parts of Worcestershire were under 6 feet (2 m) of water and the Army was brought in to help emergency services supply the inhabitants of Upton-upon-Severn which was cut off by floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 June, the first day of the floods, a road in Cropthorne near Worcester was brutally forced down by a high impact of water flowing underneath the road in a pipe.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The hole it made was 13 feet (4.0 m) deep and 33 feet (10 m) wide, traffic throughout the county was held up due to the collapsed main road.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, the region was hit by flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, the region was hit by flooding again.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The new Hull police station had to be vacated because of flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The next day, only 12 of Hull's 88 schools were still open, affecting 30,000 out of 38,000 Hull schoolchildren.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 4 July in Hull, six schools were still closed and 120 residents in residential or nursing care had been relocated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 5 July, an estimated 35,000 people in streets containing 17,000 homes had been affected by flooding in Hull and by the next day more than 10,000 homes had been evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Hull City Council estimated repair costs at £200 million.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, Hull City Council had checked each house in the flooded streets and stated that 6,500 homes had been flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 27 July, £2.1 million had been allocated to Hull and £600,000 to the East Riding for clean-up and immediate repairs, and £3.2 million to Hull and £1.5 million to the East Riding for further repairs to the region's estimated 101 schools suffering significant flood damage.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 3 September, figures released by Hull City Council had been revised upwards to 7,800 houses that had been flooded plus 1,300 businesses that were affected.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 15 June, towns and villages in North Yorkshire were flooded, with Knaresborough, Harrogate and York being particularly affected.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The A59 road at Kex Gill was closed due to a landslip where 100 tonnes (110 tons) of earth slid down the hillside and trapped a couple in their car.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Scarborough, the main A171 Scalby Road flooded outside Scarborough Hospital, and the ornamental lake at Peasholm Park overtopped its banks and poured down Peasholm Gap into North Bay.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Near Catterick, North Yorkshire, a 17-year-old soldier on a training exercise from Catterick Garrison died after being swept away whilst crossing Risedale Beck, Hipswell Moor.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 June, flooding affected Middlesbrough.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Pickering was flooded after Pickering Beck overflowed its banks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Pensioners were stranded in the town's swimming pool and rescued by lifeboat.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, Sheffield suffered extensive damage as the River Don overtopped its banks, causing widespread flooding in the Don Valley area of the city.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 14-year-old boy was swept away by the swollen River Sheaf, a 68-year-old man died after attempting to cross a flooded road in Sheffield city centre, and several cattle were washed away, found up to 3.5 miles (5.6 km) across fields in some areas of cultivated land.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Meadowhall shopping centre was closed due to flooding with some shops remaining closed downstairs until late September and Sheffield Wednesday's ground Hillsborough was under 6 feet (1.83 m) of water.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A number of people were rescued by RAF helicopters from buildings in the Brightside area, while in the Millhouses Park area to the southwest of the city the River Sheaf overtopped its banks causing widespread damage.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] There was also widespread flooding in Barnsley, Doncaster and Rotherham, with much of these towns cut off.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 26 June, the waters in some parts of Sheffield and the surrounding area receded, and over 700 villagers from Catcliffe, near Rotherham's Ulley reservoir were evacuated after cracks appeared in the dam.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Emergency services from across England pumped millions of gallons of water from the reservoir to ease the pressure on the damaged dam, and the nearby M1 Motorway was closed between junctions 32 and 36 as a precaution.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June, the Army moved into the Doncaster area after the River Don overtopped its banks and threatened the area around what was Thorpe Marsh Power Station.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A man was incorrectly reported missing near the village of Adwick le Street near Doncaster.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June and on 25 June, the villages of Scissett and Clayton West and other parts of Kirklees were flooded by the River Dearne, the second time worse than the first.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Six elderly women, including a 91-year-old, were stranded in their homes.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During the Wakefield flood, hundreds of homes were evacuated in the Agbrigg area of Wakefield and looting was feared, but by 1 July only four looters had been arrested in the city and were later released on bail.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The village of Collingham (near Wetherby) was particularly affected by the flooding, and one house was looted.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Wales was hit by flooding in June and July, with the Eastern areas most badly affected.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was Wales's wettest June since 1998, and its second wettest since 1914.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The preserved counties and principal areas affected are given below.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, roads including the A5 were impassable at Corwen in Denbighshire, a river overflowed at Worthenbury in Flintshire, and properties were affected in Wrexham.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In North Wales, a man was rescued by fire services after he was stranded on a small island in the River Dee in Llangollen, Denbighshire.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, flash floods after torrential rain forced the closure of a secondary school in Prestatyn in Denbighshire.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Lampeter in Ceredigion was affected by flooding on 11 June and then again on 15 June.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, properties were affected in Tintern on the River Wye in Monmouthshire.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flash floods affected parts of Newport, Monmouthshire and Torfaen.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Radnorshire, 30 tonnes of debris and earth blocked the only road out of Barland near Presteigne on 23 July.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Brecknockshire, the River Wye burst its banks in Builth Wells on 1 July, the saturated ground later causing chaos at the Royal Welsh Show in Llanelwedd on 24 July.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flash floods affected the Vale of Glamorgan, causing schools to be evacuated, roads to be closed, and boats used to rescue people from their homes in Barry.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Northern Ireland was hit by flooding in the June and July floods and it was Northern Ireland's wettest June since 1958.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The non-administrative counties and districts affected are given below.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, the Knockmore campus of the Lisburn Institute in Lisburn was affected by flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 2 July, houses were flooded and two people evacuated from their home in Cushendall in Antrim after the River Dall burst its banks following heavy rain.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 16 July, parts of Belfast International Airport near Aldergrove in Antrim were flooded by a freak thunderstorm leaving 10 planes unable to land, landslides closed the Antrim Coast Road near Ballygally, Larne, and people were trapped in their cars in Portrush, Coleraine.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, there was severe flooding around Bangor in North Down, Saintfield, Crossgar and Ballynahinch in Down and Newtownards and Comber in Ards, with shops in Crossgar centre flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Magherafelt was affected by flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 16 July, roads in Aghadowey, Coleraine and Portstewart, Coleraine were rendered impassable by floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Omagh and Dungannon were affected by flooding, with a Dunnes supermarket evacuated in Omagh.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Scotland was hit by flooding in June and July, with the Scottish Lowlands most badly affected.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, the Met Office issued torrential rain warnings for Scotland and it was Scotland's wettest June since 1938.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The non-administrative counties and council areas affected are given below.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 21 June, about 2000 homes were left without electricity and properties were affected as flash floods hit Kilmarnock.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, flooding affected Kilmarnock again, the River Irvine burst its banks in Newmilns, and flash floods affected roads including the M77.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, floods wrecked homes in Closeburn, power was cut off at Eaglesfield, and roads were closed at Moffat and Lochmaben.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 July, rain cancelled the one-day international cricket match between Scotland and Pakistan in Edinburgh and by 3 July parts of Midlothian were flooded, the worst-hit areas including residential areas in Dalkeith and Mayfield.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 June, heavy storms flooded roads and dumped debris on the railway line in Glasgow.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The same day, torrential rain caused a landslide just south of Lesmahagow, closing the M74.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, a landslide caused by floodwater disrupted traffic on the A941 Rothes to Aberlour road in Moray.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June rain forced the 108-year-old Beltane Festival in Peebles to be held indoors for the first time.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Following the flooding in late June, the rescue effort was described by the Fire Brigades Union as the "biggest in peacetime Britain".
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Following the flooding in July, the RAF said it was carrying out its biggest-ever peacetime rescue operation, with six Sea King helicopters from as far afield as RAF St Mawgan in Cornwall, RAF Valley in Anglesey and RAF Leconfield in the East Riding of Yorkshire rescuing up to 120 people.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] An RAF heavy lift Chinook helicopter was also employed to move aggregate to reinforce the banks of the River Don.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency described the situation as "critical".
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 4x4 Response groups from throughout the UK assisted councils and blue light services during and in the immediate aftermath of the flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During the recovery phase a number of responders from around the UK 4x4 Response assisted the Red Cross in the distribution of fresh drinking water in the Gloucestershire area after mains drinking water was contaminated.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Health Protection Agency advised people that the risk of contracting any illness was low but that it was best to avoid coming into direct contact with flood water.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] There were no reported cases of any outbreaks.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In some areas bottled water was handed out where sewage works got flooded.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The floods caused widespread crop damage, especially broccoli, carrots, peas and potatoes.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In parts of Lincolnshire it was estimated that 40% of the pea crop may have been damaged, with other crops also suffering major losses.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Prices of vegetables were expected to rise in the following months.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Environment Agency chief executive Baroness Young said that about £1 billion a year was needed to improve flood defences.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Association of British Insurers has estimated the total bill for the June and July floods as £3 billion.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, Environment Secretary Hilary Benn announced that the Government would increase the spending on risk management and flood defences by £200 million to £800 million by 2010–11.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During Prime Minister's Questions in the House of Commons later that month, Prime Minister Gordon Brown promised £46 million in aid to flood-hit councils and £800 million rise in annual spending on flood protection by 2010–11, confirming Hilary Benn's announcement.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Brown also pledged to push insurance firms to make payouts.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, the Government convened COBRA to co-ordinate the response to the crisis.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Visiting Gloucestershire on 25 July, Mr.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Brown praised emergency services for their efforts, but added: "We've got to get the supplies stepped up.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 August 2007, Defra announced that Sir Michael Pitt would chair an independent review of the response to the flooding.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 4 September of that year the Cabinet Office website launched a comments page to let people affected by the flooding contribute their experiences to the review.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Sir Michael published his interim report on 17 December 2007.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In April 2010 the government passed the Flood and Water Management Act 2010, which implemented many of Sir Michael Pitt's recommendations.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In also brings in a new regime whereby new building activity which exacerbates flooding by reducing the capacity of land to absorb water will need to be accompanied by the construction of sustainable drainage systems such as grassy roofs, ponds and soakaways.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Hull City Council was criticised for not insuring the city's libraries, schools and other public buildings.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In response, Hull City Council said that "Many councils do not have the feature in their budget", but other flood-hit councils were insured.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was thought that council tax payers would be left with the bill, as emergency Government funding would not cover it.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In June, councillors in Hull claimed that the city was being forgotten and had the floods occurred in the Home Counties, help would have arrived much more quickly.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] One in five homes in Hull was damaged and 90 out of the city's 105 schools suffered some damage.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Damage to the schools alone was estimated to cost £100 million.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Bellwin scheme for providing aid after natural disasters was criticised as inadequate by Hull MP Diana Johnson.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The lack of media coverage of flooding in Kingston upon Hull led the city council leader Carl Minns to dub Hull "the forgotten city".
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In July, the Government came under mounting criticism of its handling of the crisis, the fact that responsibilities were spread across four departments and no single minister could be held responsible, and the fact that the Army had not been called in to assist.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In response to the criticism, Environment Secretary Hilary Benn said on BBC *Sunday AM* that "This was very, very intense rainfall, with five inches in 24 hours in some areas; even some of the best defences are going to be overwhelmed".
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] He praised the way the emergency services had dealt with "unprecedented" levels of rainfall and said he had "total confidence" in the response of the Environment Agency.
[src:river-severn/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Conservative leader David Cameron called for a public inquiry into the flooding after visiting Witney, the main town in his Oxfordshire constituency.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Between November 2019 and February 2020, severe winter flooding occurred across the United Kingdom.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The first wave of flooding occurred in November 2019, mainly affecting Yorkshire and the Humber, the East Midlands and the West Midlands.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Further isolated flooding incidents were reported in December and January, before the second main wave of flooding, caused by Storms Ciara and Dennis, occurred in February 2020.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The excessive rainfall resulted in the wettest February since records began, in 1766, in England and Wales with an average of 169.6 millimetres (6.68 in) falling across the regions, beating the record from 1833.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Most of England received above average rainfall during October 2019, with some catchments receiving over double the average monthly total.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Soils were wetter than average for the time of year across most of the country by the end of October.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Monthly mean river flows were classed as exceptionally high at just over a third of indicator sites.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Early on 8 November, heavy and prolonged rainfall fell on these saturated catchments across the southern Peak District causing flash floods and rivers to burst their banks.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A week later on 14 November a further low pressure system brought more heavy rain to areas further south, raising water levels along on the rivers Severn and Avon.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Met Office reported that Sheffield had 84 mm (3.3 in) of rain in just over the 36 hours which preceded the flood.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] This is almost the same as the monthly average for November.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November Supertram services were terminated at Meadowhall South/Tinsley tram stop over fears that floodwater would put the Tinsley tram bridge in danger.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 November, shoppers spent the night inside Meadowhall shopping centre as floods surrounded the complex.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Rain continued overnight leading to a major incident being declared in Sheffield.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Millhouses public park, where in the 2007 floods a boy was swept to his death, was closed, due to concerns about the level of the River Sheaf, a tributary of the Don.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 November junction 34 of the M1 was closed.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding throughout the regions affected rail services from Sheffield.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November flooding at Denby Dale resulted in trains being unable to run between Huddersfield and Sheffield via Penistone.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November train services between Sheffield and Worksop were cancelled because of floods as was the East Midlands Trains service from Sheffield to London St Pancras via the Midland Main Line.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November the TransPennine Express services between Sheffield and Scunthorpe was suspended because of floods in Kirk Sandall, Doncaster.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Hope Valley Line service was also disrupted due to flooding at nearby Edale.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding of railway lines in Rotherham also affected train services from Sheffield.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 November the Met Office reported its Sheffield weather station had recorded its wettest ever autumn, "With 15 days [of November] still to go, the site has already recorded 427.6 mm of rain.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The railway tracks at Rotherham Central railway station, used by both Arriva Rail North railway services and the Sheffield Supertram tram-train, were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Trains were unable to run between Sheffield and Gainsborough Central or Lincoln Central.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Sheffield to Leeds (via Moorthorpe) route was also suspended.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November M1 junction 32, the M18 turn-off was reduced to two lanes due to floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 November flooding led to an oil spillage which led to the RSPCA having to rescue 60 swans.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November it was reported that all Supertram services were operating as normal with the exception of the tram-train.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Plans to switch on the Christmas lights in Rotherham were cancelled until further notice because of the floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Rotherham Parkgate retail park was also closed because of flooding with 85% of the shops re-opening on 16 November, this later caused the temporary closure of a local Burger King.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The River Don flooded in Doncaster, South Yorkshire, reaching record levels with severe flood warnings continuing into 12 November.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 11 November there were 5 severe flood warnings in place for Kirk Bramwith, South Bramwith, Willow Bridge, Bentley and Fishlake, with residents of Fishlake, Thorpe in Balne, Trumfleet and Bentley being asked to evacuate their homes.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Fishlake local resident, Grant Berry appeared on BBC News stating, "The village had not flooded in over 100 years" as he evacuated his home.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 11 November the Environment Agency deployed four pumps at Fishlake in an attempt to reduce the depth of flood-water and an RAF Chinook was used to convey aggregate to shore-up the banks of drainage channels east of Bentley.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Fishlake residents were critical of the Environment Agency which had stated that on Friday 8 November at 5:00 pm there was no flood warning.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Even when the village had flooded by 9:00 pm the Environment Agency had still not issued a flood warning.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November John Curtin, executive director of flood and coastal risk management at the Environment Agency, said 38 pumps had been used in homes in Fishlake to reduce the inundation.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Arriva Rail North told customers not to travel on the Doncaster to Scunthorpe route.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] CrossCountry diverted its trains away from Doncaster.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The floods resulted in the closure of 39 roads in the Doncaster area on 11 November.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November Doncaster Metropolitan Borough Council issued a list of 26 roads still closed due to the flood.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In the Don Valley area, Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn visited Conisborough and Doncaster and viewed the property damage with local MP Caroline Flint, calling on Prime Minister Boris Johnson to declare the floods a national emergency so immediate financial help could be provided to families in need.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November the River Dearne burst its banks, flooding the pub and restaurant, *The Mill of the Black Monks*, thought to be Barnsley's oldest pub.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The building mostly dates back to 1150 AD, with some parts dating back to 700 AD.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Other nearby residences were also flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November, within Barnsley twelve roads were closed due to floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Residents and businesses in the Lundwood and Low Valley areas of Barnsley were flooded and the B6096, Station Road at Wombwell was affected by severe flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November three roads remained closed due to floodwater, New Road (from Tingle Bridge Lane junction to the roundabout at Lions Lodge) and Smithy Bridge Lane at Hemingfield, and Birds Nest Lane at Penistone.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November run-off from fields closed the A63, the only link between Hull and the M62 motorway.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The road re-opened on 15 November although a significant number of roads remained closed in the Hull area, including sections of the A164.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 November flooding of railway lines on part of the East Coast Mainline led to delays on the Leeds to London service, with all LNER electric locomotive hauled services being cancelled.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] At least seven roads in West Yorkshire were closed, including the M606 Northbound main carriageway at junction 3, part of the A641 and some of the A646 Halifax to Burnley route.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The moveable weir at Knostrop, part of the River Aire flood alleviation scheme, was lowered to reduce the water level upstream.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Derwent flooded, and parts of Matlock were submerged as a month's worth of rainfall fell in a day.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A woman swept away when wading through fast moving floodwaters and found dead later the same day was named as a former High Sheriff of Derbyshire, Annie Hall.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] During a visit to Matlock, Boris Johnson, the British prime minister said the floods were "not like something we need to escalate to the level of a national emergency".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 November a number of car parks at Chatsworth House were closed, with access to the Christmas market restricted to pre-booked customers and 'Friends of Chatsworth'.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Also on 12 November, flooding at Edale led to the closure of the Hope Valley rail service from Sheffield to Manchester Piccadilly.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the railtracks at Draycott flooded, leading to delays on journeys from Derby to Long Eaton on the Midland Main Line, and the Matlock to Newark Castle lines were also affected.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 7 November the River Ryton burst its banks resulting in major incidents being declared in Worksop.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Residents and Bassetlaw District Council leader, Simon Greaves, were critical of the Canal and River Trust (CRT) for not opening The Canch sluice gate.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] This sluice feeds excess water to the Chesterfield Canal via a channel.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The sluice was eventually opened by a firefighter.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The initial response of the CRT to requests to open the gate was to say no flood alert had been issued for the Ryton, according to a resident of the Riverside Caravan Park.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] When CRT engineers visited the sluice gate they refused to enter the building housing the sluice, saying the building was 'unsafe'.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The CRT is responsible for the sluice gate though the building is owned by the council.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November the CRT released a statement stating that the sluice was not designed to drain the river.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] It said "Definitively, it would not have alleviated the flooding in the town.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The water would have stayed in the area as the feeder, canal and river all run in parallel a very short distance apart".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Residents of mobile homes in Newark were evacuated on 9 November over fears that the River Trent would burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency issued a flood warning for Retford and moved pumps into the Retford Beck area in an attempt to prevent the flooding of homes.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Mansfield the heavy rain also caused a mudslide which resulted in 35 homes being evacuated.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Transport was affected in the county with road and rail closures.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] East Midlands Railway services on the Nottingham to Mansfield and Worksop routes were disrupted due to flooding on the railway line.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] More than seven roads were closed in the Nottinghamshire area.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The rail service between Shirebrook and Worksop, on the Robin Hood Line was also disrupted.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November East Midlands Railway said a flooded railway line near Loughborough had disrupted services between Lincoln, Nottingham and Leicester.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The bus operator, Nottingham City Transport reported that flooding had affected fourteen of its routes, with some bus stops not being served.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] More than 1,000 acres (400 ha) in Lincolnshire were underwater when the Barlings Eau burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Twelve flood warnings were issued in the county and some farms were cut off.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] About 30 residents were evacuated from the Short Ferry Caravan Park near to Bardney, which is close to the Barlings Eau.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 November homes in the Cherry Willingham area of Lincoln were inundated as the River Witham burst its banks, and the area around the Brayford Pool in the centre of Lincoln was flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A number of roads were closed in the county including parts of the A1 (northbound), parts of the A46 and parts of the A631.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Bransby Horses, an animal sanctuary near Lincoln, was told by the Environment Agency to close their drain valves and flood their site.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The sanctuary, which is located on the River Till washlands has long-standing agreement with the agency to do so in order to reduce flooding in Lincoln.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The washlands help protect 7,000 homes and businesses in and around Lincoln.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Bransby Horses site has seen human sewage and four feet of water on their fields with 40% of the grazing land unsafe for at least the next six months (from November 2019).
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Over one hundred of the four hundred and fifty horses, donkeys, ponies and mules were moved to the sanctuary's site in Barlings, which was bought specifically to deal with emergency evacuations of the Bransby site.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Grimsby the River Freshney reached record levels flooding homes in nearby Healing.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Riverhead pumping station, operated by Associated British Ports attempted to pump as much of the Freshney's water into Alexandra Dock as was possible using all three Archimedes screws at the pumping station simultaneously.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November nine roads in Lincolnshire remained closed because of flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On the same day an embankment supporting Fodderdyke Bank, a road at New Leake, near Boston, collapsed into the adjacent drain.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The drain takes excess rainfall to pumping stations at Lade Bank and Hobhole where it is discharged into The Wash.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] By 15 November Environment Agency data from monitoring station at Brigg had recorded 104.6 mm of rainfall since 1 November, more than twice the 50 mm average for the month.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Both the New River Ancholme (constructed in 1635) and the Old River Ancholme had over-topped their banks flooding parts of Brigg.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Fifty homes across North Lincolnshire were flooded, according to figures released by North Lincolnshire council.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the River Cole burst its banks causing flooding in the Hall Green area.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] West Midlands Railway services between Birmingham Snow Hill and Stratford-Upon-Avon were cancelled.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On the same day British Transport Police, Network Rail and staff at Birmingham New Street station advised passengers not to travel by rail unless it was absolutely necessary.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November in Shropshire nine schools were closed because of floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency issued three flood warnings for the county, two on the River Severn and one on the River Teme.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Sections of the A49 and A488 were closed as were a number of minor roads, particularly in the south of the county.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November four schools remained closed.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November rail services between Shrewsbury and Welshpool did not run due to flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the A438 at Portwaym was flooded with the local authority asking drivers to avoid it if possible and the A417 at Maund Bryan was closed after cars became stranded in floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Eighteen schools in Herefordshire were closed due to the floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] West Midlands Trains reported that the railway line between Great Malvern and Hereford was closed because of flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A landslip led to the closure of the B4234 between Kerne Bridge and Walford.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the Environment Agency issued flood warnings on all rivers in Herefordshire and the Lugg, the Teme and the Frome burst their banks, affecting a small number roads in the north of the county.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Settlements affected by flooding included the Greyfriars area, Leintwardine, Walford, Little Hereford, Ashford Carbonel, Ross-on-Wye and Hereford with the A4103 and A4113 roads also affected.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November Worcestershire County Council closed sixty-one schools because of the floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency deployed a pump at Upton-upon-Severn, Worcestershire, to remove standing water.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Parts of the A38 were closed in both directions at Stoke Heath because of flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A mudslide occurred on the road at Wilden Lane, Stourport-on-Severn although the road remained open.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Wychavon, on 14 November thirty-eight roads were closed, including parts of the, A44, A449 and A4133, with one road at Hartlebury being closed due to a mud slide.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Malvern twelve Roads were closed, in Redditch seven were closed and a further five closed in Bromsgrove.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November West Midlands Trains' services between Worcester and Birmingham were cancelled because of flooding in Bromsgrove.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November train services between Moreton-in-Marsh and Worcester Shrub Hill did not run because to flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Floods caused major disruption to transport on 15 November with over 125 roads being closed in Worcestershire, including sections of the A38, A44, A442, A443, A448 and A449.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Bus services between Tenbury and Worcester were cancelled as were many school bus services.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Evesham, river levels were at their highest since the 2007 United Kingdom floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency reported that between twenty-five and thirty properties close to the Avon in Evesham were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 16 November over twenty-five roads remained closed throughout the county.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Three Counties Farming Conference at the Three Counties Showground, Malvern was cancelled on 15 November due to road conditions.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November in Sambourne, near Coughton, in Warwickshire vehicle drivers had to be rescued from flood water.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding on the tracks disrupted rail services to Leamington Spa.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Twenty-seven schools across the county were closed on 14 November due to flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the Shipston river gauge on the River Stour reached a high level which prompted the Environment Agency to issue flood alerts for Halford, Crimscote, Alderminster, Preston-on-Stour, Ailstone, Atherstone-on-Stour and Clifford Chambers.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Agency said three flood warnings have been issued for the River Dene and Stour with a total of 20 flood alerts in place in the county.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November the River Avon broke its banks causing flooding across Warwickshire and Worcestershire.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency issued flood warnings for Stratford-upon-Avon, Evesham, Bidford-on-Avon, Warwick, and Leamington Spa.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Stratford-upon-Avon, temporary flood barriers were installed near the town centre.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Floodwater reached the road outside Anne Hathaway's Cottage in Shottery, Stratford-upon-Avon.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the CrossCountry trains services to Banbury were affected by surface water on the line to Leamington Spa.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Oxfordshire County Council announced that flooded roads were impassable between Woodeaton, Elsfield, and Marston, and that the road between Waterperry and Worminghall was flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Vehicle drivers were turned away from Wendlebury due to flood water.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November there were 20 flood alerts in place across the county.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November flood alerts were issued for the River Thames and River Cherwell through Oxford.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Surface water flooding in the Beachampton area of Buckinghamshire led to vehicles being stranded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November nine roads were closed in the county, with many more affected by surface water flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The 15 November races at Cheltenham Racecourse were abandoned due to the rainfall.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] By 16 November the number of closed roads had risen to fourteen.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The River Avon and River Severn burst their banks in Tewkesbury flooding a number of properties.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Twelve roads remained closed on 17 November, with the B4234 at Kerne Bridge being closed due to a landslip.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding was reported across southern England from 18 to 22 December, caused by repeated intense cold fronts moving across the area, accumulating high rainfall totals.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In total, 91 flood warnings and 237 flood alerts were issued by the Environment Agency.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In many areas, more than 50 mm (2.0 in) of rain fell in less than 36 hours.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding caused widespread travel disruption during the pre-Christmas rush, which is traditionally the busiest time of year for public transport in the United Kingdom.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Buckinghamshire, there were reports of cars becoming stranded on flooded roads, and a mother and her three sons had to be rescued from a stranded vehicle.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The River Great Ouse burst its banks in St Ives, Cambridgeshire.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding was also reported in Reading after the River Loddon burst its banks and the River Thames reached high levels.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Great Western Railway and South Western Railway (2017-2025)South Western Railway services were suspended between Guildford and Godalming after a collapsed embankment blocked a tunnel entrance.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Minor surface flooding of roads and railways was also reported in Norfolk and Suffolk.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The M23 motorway was closed in both directions between junctions 10 and 11 in West Sussex after becoming blocked by floodwater.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The River Medway in Kent burst its banks, flooding the town of Maidstone and nearby Yalding and Teston.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Yalding, visitors to a caravan site were rescued by boat after it became cut-off by rising waters.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Trains operated by Southeastern between Maidstone West and Strood, and between Tunbridge Wells and Hastings, were suspended as a result of downed trees, track damage and electricity failures.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In South West England, the Somerset Levels witnessed widespread flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Up to 53 mm (2.1 in) of rainfall was recorded in Devon and Cornwall, causing serious flooding in numerous towns and villages, particularly Hayle where a major incident was declared by police.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Up to 60 properties in Hayle were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Roads including the main A30 and railways including Great Western Railway services between Exeter St Davids and Taunton were closed or suspended, isolating much of the region from the rest of the country for several days.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A weak tornado was reported in Chertsey, Surrey on 21 December; it was filmed by a vehicle dashcam crossing both carriageways of the M25 motorway before striking a residential area, damaging homes, gardens and vehicles.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Several houses suffered severe roof damage as a result of the tornado and many cars were damaged beyond repair.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Subsequent damage assessment rated the tornado as an F1 on the Fujita scale according to the European Severe Weather Database.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] By daybreak on 16 February, severe flooding was reported across the East Midlands, including Ilkeston and Lowdham; a major incident was declared by the local council in the latter village.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Across Leicestershire, dozens of roads were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Loughborough, the River Soar and its tributary the Wood Brook both burst their banks, flooding residential areas of the town.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding was also reported in nearby Sileby, where the flood siren was sounded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding near Draycott in Derbyshire resulted in the temporarily closure of the Midland Main Line between Derby and Long Eaton, affecting East Midlands Railway services between Sheffield and London St Pancras.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding of homes was also reported in nearby Rainworth and Radcliffe-on-Trent.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Later on 16 February, the main road through the Derbyshire village of Repton was closed after floodwaters made it impassable, and passing cars had been splashing water into homes and businesses.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] There was also some minor flooding from the River Derwent in Derby itself, including at the Derby Rugby Club.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Pumps were deployed to protect the town of Retford from flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] At around 07:30 local time on 16 February, the 06:41 Thameslink service from Cambridge to Potters Bar, operated by a Class 700 unit, struck a tree on the railway that had been downed by high winds near Royston in Hertfordshire.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] There were no injuries in the incident, and the train suffered only minor damage.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The tree was removed by 08:45, allowing the train to continue to its destination, after which it was taken out of service and returned to the depot for safety inspections.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Rail services subsequently resumed on the Thameslink line with heavy delays due to storm-related speed restrictions as a safety precaution following the Royston incident.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In the London area, adverse weather conditions resulted in the postponement of the Women's FA Cup football matches between Arsenal and Lewes and between Crystal Palace and Brighton & Hove Albion; the latter is contested as the M23 derby.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In the New Forest area of Hampshire, a DPDgroup delivery van was washed away from a swollen ford, with the driver making a lucky escape after the van became lodged under a tree.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In nearby Romsey, temporary flood barriers were erected to protect more than 200 at-risk properties from flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Severe flooding was reported in the Dartmoor area on 16 February, with the surrounding towns and villages of Bovey Tracey, Heathfield, Newton Abbot, Littlehempston and Highweek particularly affected.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Part of the South West Coast Path near Swanage in Dorset was closed after it was blocked by a landslide, and nearby cliffs were deemed to be dangerously unstable.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Storm Dennis brought historic flooding to South Wales, particularly to areas of the Valleys covered by the Met Office red severe weather warning for rain; many areas saw more than a month's worth of rainfall within a period of less than 48 hours.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Maerdy, Rhondda, more than 160 mm (6.3 in) of rain was recorded in a 48-hour period starting at midday on 14 February.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] As a result of widespread serious flooding and landslides, South Wales Police declared a major incident across the region, and the South Wales Fire and Rescue Service responded to more than 1,400 calls in a 12-hour period.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Hundreds of homes and businesses were damaged, and one person was killed after falling into the River Tawe near Swansea.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Natural Resources Wales issued two severe flood warnings, meaning an imminent danger to life was occurring, during the course of Storm Dennis – these covered the River Neath around Aberdulais and the River Taff around Pontypridd.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] More than 80 lower-level flood warnings were issued across Wales.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Large-scale evacuations of villages in the River Usk and River Wye floodplains were co-ordinated by emergency services on 16 February in anticipation of serious flooding.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Further evacuations took place in Monmouthshire and Neath Port Talbot, with the entire village of Tonna being evacuated by bus.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The levels of the River Wye at Monmouth reached a record high on 18 February.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] At Whitebrook beside the Wye, a woman was rescued after spending 12 hours on the roof of her submerged car.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Hundreds of people were evacuated from Nantgarw.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Emergency services were also stretched by the need to carry out rescues from vehicles and properties as people were caught out by rapidly rising floodwaters, including from homes in Crickhowell, Powys.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Additionally, the main road bridge in Crickhowell was severely damaged.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Severe flooding occurred in the town of Pontypridd and in parts of Cardiff as the River Taff reached its highest level in recorded history, flooding homes and businesses and disrupting transport.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Houses in Pontypridd were inundated by more than 5 feet (1.5 m) of water, with residents being rescued from the upper floors; riverside walls collapsed and parked vehicles were washed away, adding damaging debris to the fast-flowing waters and exacerbating the situation in Pontypridd.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The town centre was completely inundated, and a major emergency was declared across the wider Rhondda Cynon Taf council area.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Some of the other badly affected settlements were Cwm in Blaenau Gwent and Argoed in Caerphilly, where emergency services spent considerable time unsuccessfully trying to pump floodwaters away from houses.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Further flooding of homes and businesses was reported in the settlements of New Tredegar, Bedwas, Newbridge, Risca and Llanbradach.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Transport for Wales reported severe disruption to rail services across Wales and beyond into England, including key routes from Cardiff Central, Aberystwyth, Holyhead and Carmarthen to Birmingham New Street and Manchester Piccadilly.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In addition to flooding, dozens of landslides were reported across Wales.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Debris from landslides in the upper valleys, including mud and large rocks, was carried down into the town of Mountain Ash by floodwaters, worsening the damage from flooding there.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Tylorstown, a large mudslide on a steep hillside above the village was caught on video; on the other side of the same mountain in Llanwonno, more than 300 m (980 ft) of hillside suddenly collapsed, damaging telecommunications equipment.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A man was also swept into the Teme near Tenbury Wells, but was later rescued; more than 130 homes in the village were flooded, where waters peaked higher than the previous historic floods of 2007.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Hereford, the River Wye reached its highest level in recorded history, and the major incident declaration was subsequently expanded to cover Herefordshire and Shropshire.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Across Herefordshire, landslides and high river levels damaged roads and bridges.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Ludlow, Shropshire, more than 50 homes were flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Properties were also flooded in the centre of Shrewsbury as the River Severn burst its banks.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency described the flooding across parts of the West Midlands as "unprecedented", and warned that excess runoff from the upper reaches of the Severn in Wales meant that the flooding in the lower Severn valley would likely be prolonged for at least three days.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Bradford on 16 February, the M606 motorway was closed in both directions due to flooding on one of the carriageways, which persisted despite efforts overnight to pump the road clear.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding in the Calder Valley, which had been severely impacted by Storm Ciara the weekend before, was less than initially anticipated.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The River Calder rose to very high levels but did not break its banks in Todmorden, Hebden Bridge or Mytholmroyd, unlike the previous weekend, and only minor surface water flooding was reported across Calderdale in general.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Voluntary flood wardens in the Calder Valley described it as "an unexpectedly steady night".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] There was flooding in Boroughbridge as the River Ure peaked at 15.12 m (49.6 ft), breaking its banks in several places.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Flooding was reported in the Sheffield area.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Surface water flooded sliproads onto the Sheffield Parkway in Handsworth, which then had to be closed as a car became stranded in the water.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] River levels were very high, especially along the River Don, resulting in some minor riverside flooding in the Lower Don Valley between the city centre and Meadowhall.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In Rotherham, the Don and Rother burst their banks, flooding the railway around Rotherham Central station and resulting in the suspension of Arriva Rail North and Sheffield Supertram services.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Additionally, the Snake Pass road to Manchester was closed as a result of landslides.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 11 November Prime Minister Boris Johnson called a Cobra meeting over the governments response to the flooding which came after leader of the opposition, Jeremy Corbyn sent a letter to Johnson calling on him to hold a Cobra meeting.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 13 November the Prime Minister visited Stainforth, South Yorkshire, as 100 soldiers from the Light Dragoons and 2 Royal Anglian were deployed to the area.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 11 November the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government initiated the Bellwin scheme, designed to provide compensation to local authorities for some of the initial costs they incur as a result of flooding in Yorkshire, Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 14 November the Environment Agency estimated that 830 properties had been flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] This figure was challenged by *The Guardian*, which had contacted local authorities in Yorkshire, Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire and Lincolnshire, and found that at least 1,758 properties had been flooded.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 November the Prime Minister announced households and business owners significantly affected by recent floods would receive relief on their council tax and business rates for at least the next three months.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Chris Read, leader of Rotherham Council was critical of the lack of consultation with local authorities.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A reporter from the *Rotherham Advertiser* sought clarity from the Government on how the relief would work, including eligibility criteria.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] A spokeswoman for the government admitted the criteria are "yet to be decided".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 21 February 2020 Prince Charles visited Pontypridd and met with local residents.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Rock band the Manic Street Preachers donated £3,000 towards those dealing with the flood damage, and a fundraising page, set up by local MP Alex Davies-Jones, raised more than £20,000.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] In April 2020 Amanda Blanc, a former chair the Association of British Insurers, was appointed to review flood insurance for those affected in Doncaster following the November 2019 floods.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The report was published in November 2020.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June 2020 Dan Jarvis, Mayor of Sheffield City Region Combined Authority, wrote to Boris Johnson and government ministers asking for action on improving flood defences in "close collaboration with devolved authorities." The government had made promises for action seven months earlier.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The government responded by saying it was working to "identify suitable arrangements" for a "Yorkshire floods roundtable".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Many residents and businesses in the Fishlake area were still not able to return home or were in need of repair work.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] On 28 January 2022 a flood protection plan for South Yorkshire was launched.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The £400m *Connected by Water Action Plan*, which received £110m of government funding, involves 100 projects.
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] Dan Jarvis MP and South Yorkshire mayor said he believed the plan could "break the cycle".
[src:river-severn/2019-20-united-kingdom-floods] The plan includes the construction walls and barriers and also uses a range of natural methods to slow river flow, such as tree planting and land management to create more space for water.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] This is a complete **list of acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for the year 1842**.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Note that the first parliament of the United Kingdom was held in 1801; parliaments between 1707 and 1800 were either parliaments of Great Britain or of Ireland).
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] For acts passed up until 1707, see the list of acts of the Parliament of England and the list of acts of the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] For acts passed from 1707 to 1800, see the list of acts of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] See also the list of acts of the Parliament of Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] For acts of the devolved parliaments and assemblies in the United Kingdom, see the list of acts of the Scottish Parliament, the list of acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly, and the list of acts and measures of Senedd Cymru; see also the list of acts of the Parliament of Northern Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] The number shown after each act's title is its chapter number.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Acts passed before 1963 are cited using this number, preceded by the year(s) of the reign during which the relevant parliamentary session was held; thus the Union with Ireland Act 1800 is cited as "39 & 40 Geo.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] 67", meaning the 67th act passed during the session that started in the 39th year of the reign of George III and which finished in the 40th year of that reign.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Note that the modern convention is to use Arabic numerals in citations (thus "41 Geo.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Acts of the last session of the Parliament of Great Britain and the first session of the Parliament of the United Kingdom are both cited as "41 Geo.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Some of these acts have never had a short title.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] Some of these acts have a short title given to them by later acts, such as by the Short Titles Act 1896.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] The second session of the 14th Parliament of the United Kingdom, which met from 3 February 1842 until 12 August 1842.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] This session was also traditionally cited as **5 Vict.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act better to provide for the Application to the Service of the Year One thousand eight hundred and forty-one of the Sums granted in the Two last Sessions of Parliament.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to enable His Royal Highness Albert Edward Prince of Wales to make Leases and Grants of Land and Hereditaments, Parcel of His said Royal Highness' Duchy of Cornwall, or annexed to the same; and for the other Purposes therein mentioned.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to confirm an Act of the legislature of Van Diemen's Land, for authorizing the Levy of certain Duties of Customs and on Spirits.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to provide for the Increase of the Number of Bishoprics and Archdeaconries in the West Indies, and to amend the several Acts relating thereto.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] to amend the Laws relating to Loan Societies.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for vacating any Presentment for rebuilding the Gaol of Newgate in Dublin, and any Contract between the Commissioners for rebuilding the said Gaol and the Contractor.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to explain the Acts for the better Regulation of certain Apprentices.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to apply the Sum of Eight Millions out of the Consolidated Fund to the Service of the Year One thousand eight hundred and forty-two.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to authorize the Advance of Money out of the Consolidated Fund to a limited Amount for carrying on Public Works and Fisheries, and Employment of the Poor; and to amend the Acts authorizing the Issue of Exchequer Bills for the like Purposes.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for appointing Commissioners to inquire as to the Issue, Receipt, Circulation, and Possession of certain forged Exchequer Bills.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for punishing Mutiny and Desertion, and for the better Payment of the Army and their Quarters.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for the Regulation of Her Majesty's Royal Marine Forces while on shore.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Laws for the Importation of Corn.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to impose an additional Duty on Spirits, and to repeal the Allowance on Spirits made from Malt only, in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue, until the End of the Session of Parliament next after the Thirty-first Day of July One thousand eight hundred and forty-four, certain of the Allowances of the Duty of Excise on Soap used in Manufactures.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for preventing, until the First Day of May One thousand eight hundred and forty-five, Ships clearing out from any Port in British North America, or in the Settlement of Honduras, from loading any Part of their Cargo of Timber upon Deck.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to explain and amend the Acts regulating the Sale of Parish Property; and to make further Provision for the Discharge of Debts, Liabilities, and Engagements incurred by or on behalf of Parishes.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for enabling Her Majesty's Commissioners of Woods to purchase certain Lands for Victoria Park.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for raising the Sum of Nine millions one hundred thousand Pounds by Exchequer Bills, for the Service of the Year One thousand eight hundred and forty-two.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for consolidating the Queen's Bench, Fleet, and Marshalsea Prisons, and for regulating the Queen's Prison.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue, until the Thirty-first Day of July One thousand eight hundred and forty-three, and to the End of the then Session of Parliament, the several Acts for regulating Turnpike Roads in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] as repeals the Allowance on Spirits made from Malt only in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to alter and amend the Law relating to ecclesiastical Houses of Residence.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for better enabling Incumbents of Ecclesiastical Benefices to demise the Lands belonging to their Benefices on Farming Leases.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to assimilate the Law in Ireland, as to the Punishment of Death, to the Law in England; to abolish the Punishment of Death in certain Cases in Ireland, and to substitute other Punishments in lieu thereof.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for establishing a Prison at Pentonville.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to provide Regulations for preparing and using Roasted Malt in colouring Beer.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for better recording Fines and Recoveries in Wales and Cheshire.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] as relates to the Execution of Civil Bill Decrees for the Possession of Land in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for granting to Her Majesty, until the Fifth Day of July One thousand eight hundred and forty-three, certain Duties on Sugar imported into the United Kingdom, for the Service of the Year One thousand eight hundred and forty-two.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for granting to Her Majesty Duties on Profits arising from Property, Professions, Trades, and Offices, until the Sixth Day of April, One thousand eight hundred and forty-five.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for regulating the Sale of Waste Land belonging to the Crown in the Australian Colonies.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue until the Fifth Day of April One thousand eight hundred and forty-four Compositions for Assessed Taxes; and to amend the Laws relating to the Land and Assessed Taxes.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to define the Jurisdiction of Justices in General and Quarter Sessions of the Peace.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Law relating to Advances bonâ fide made to Agents intrusted with Goods.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for carrying into effect the Treaty between Her Majesty and the Argentine Confederation for the Abolition of the Slave Trade.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for the more effectual Suppression of the Slave Trade.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for better and more effectually carrying into effect Treaties and Conventions with Foreign States for suppressing the Slave Trade.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for the Transfer of Licences and Regulation of Public Houses.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for the Regulation of Municipal Corporations in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Laws relating to the Customs.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to provide for the Relief of the Poor in the Forest of Dean and other Extra-parochial Places in and near the Hundred of Saint Briavel's in the County of Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Laws for the Regulation of the Trade of the British Possessions abroad.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue, until the First Day o£ October One thousand eight hundred and forty-three, the Exemption of Inhabitants of Parishes, Townships, and Villages from Liability to be rated as such, in respect of Stock in Trade or other Property, to the Relief of the Poor.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for providing for the further Security and Protection of Her Majesty's Person.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to indemnify Witnesses who may give Evidence before the Lords Spiritual and Temporal on a Bill to exclude the Borough of Sudbury from sending Burgesses to serve in Parliament.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to encourage the Establishment of District Courts and Prisons.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Acts for the commutation of tithes in England and Wales, and to continue the Officers appointed under the said Acts for a Time to be limited.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for the better Regulation of Railways and for the Conveyance of Troops.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for further amending the Laws relating to the Customs.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue until the Thirty-first Day of July One thousand eight hundred and forty-seven, and to the End of the then next Session of Parliament, the Poor Law Commission; and for the further Amendment of the Laws relating to the Poor in England.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for further suspending, until the First Day of October One thousand eight hundred and forty-three, the Operation of the new Arrangement of Dioceses, so far as it affects the existing Ecclesiastical Jurisdictions.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue until the First Day of August One thousand eight hundred and forty-three an Act for authorizing Her Majesty to carry into immediate Execution, by Orders in Council, any Treaties for the Suppression of the Slave Trade.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue until the First Day of October One thousand eight hundred and forty three certain Turnpike Acts.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to provide for the better Government of South Australia.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for enabling the Commissioners of Wide Streets to sell, and Her Majesty to purchase, certain Hereditaments in the City of Dublin, on the North Bank of the River Anna Liffey.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to continue until the First Day of August One thousand eight hundred and forty-three an Act for carrying into effect a Convention between Her Majesty and the King of the French relative to the Fisheries on the Coasts of the British Islands and of France.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to divide the Forest of Dean in the County of Gloucester into Ecclesiastical Districts.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for further regulating the Preparation and Issue of Exchequer Bills.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for the better regulating the Number of Prisoners admitted to the General Prison at Perth.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for the more effectual Prevention of Frauds and Abuses committed by Weavers, Sewers, and other Persons employed in the Linen, Hempen, Union, Cotton, Silk, and Woollen Manufactures in Ireland, and for the better Payment of their Wages.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for perpetuating Testimony in certain Cases.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Laws relating to the Payment of Out-Pensioners of Chelsea Hospital.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to establish Military Savings Banks.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to suspend until the Thirty-first Day of August One thousand eight hundred and forty-three the making of Lists and the Ballots and Enrolments for the Militia of the United Kingdom.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for amending the Law for the Trial of controverted Elections.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] "to amend the Representation of the People of Ireland," in respect of the Right of Voting in the University of Dublin.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to remove Doubts touching the Law relating to Charitable Pawn or Deposit Offices in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for the Government of New South Wales and Van Diemen's Land.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to enable Grand Juries at the ensuing Summer and Spring Assizes to make certain Presentments in Counties of Cities and Towns in Ireland; and to remove Doubts as to the Jurisdiction of Justices of the Peace in Places recently annexed to Counties at large in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for effecting an Exchange between Her Majesty and the Provost and College of Eton.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to repeal the Duties payable on Stage Carriages and on Passengers conveyed upon Railways, and certain other Stamp Duties in Great Britain, and to grant other Duties in lieu thereof; and also to amend the Laws relating to the Stamp Duties.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to grant Relief from the Duties of Assessed Taxes in certain Cases, and to provide for the assessing and charging the Proper Tax on Dividends payable out of the Revenue of Foreign States.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to transfer the Collection and Management of the Duties on Certificates to kill Game in Ireland to the Commissioners of Excise.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to assimilate the Stamp Duties in Great Britain and Ireland, and to make Regulations for collecting and managing the same, until the Tenth Day of October One thousand eight hundred and forty-five.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to abolish the Court of Saint Briavel's, and for the more easy and speedy Recovery of Small Debts within the Hundred of Saint Briavel's, in the County of Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to alter and amend the Practice and Course of Proceeding under Commissions in the Nature of Writs De lunatico inquirendo.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Law relative to legal Proceedings by certain Joint Stock Banking Companies against their own Members, and by such Members against the Companies.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for abolishing certain Offices on the Revenue Side of the Court of Exchequer in England, and for regulating the Office of Her Majesty's Remembrancer in that Court.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] for providing for the Government of His Majesty's Settlements in Western Australia on the Western Coast of New Holland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to promote the Drainage of Lands, and Improvement of Navigation and Water Power in connexion with such Drainage, in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to permit, until the Thirty-first Day of August One thousand eight hundred and forty-five, Wheat to be delivered from the Warehouse or the Vessel Duty-free, upon the previous Substitution of an equivalent Quantity of Flour or Biscuit in the Warehouse.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] to discontinue the Excise Survey on Tobacco, and to provide other Regulations in lieu thereof.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to consolidate and amend the laws relating to the services of the Ordnance Department, and the vesting and purchase of lands and hereditaments for those services, and for the defence and security of the Realm.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act for consolidating the Four Courts Marshalsea, Dublin, Sheriffs Prison, Dublin, and City Marshalsea, Dublin, and for regulating the Four Courts Marshalsea in Ireland.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to alter the Number and define the Boundaries of the several Baronies of the County of Dublin.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Law relating to Double Costs, Notices of Action, Limitations of Actions, and Pleas of the General Issue, under certain Acts of Parliament.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to amend the Laws concerning Prisons.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p01] An Act to prohibit the Employment of Women and Girls in Mines and Collieries, to regulate the Employment of Boys, and to make other Provisions relating to Persons working therein.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p02] An Act to consolidate and amend the Laws relating to the Copyright of Designs for ornamenting Articles of Manufacture.
[src:river-severn/5-6-vict-p02] to Her Majesty's Governors and Officers for the more effectual Suppression of the Importation of Slaves into India by Sea.
