[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In 1896, Housman published *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of poems marked by the author's pessimism and preoccupation with early death, which gradually acquired a wide readership and appealed particularly to a younger audience during World War I.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Another collection, entitled *Last Poems*, appeared in 1922.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry became popular for musical settings.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Following his death, further poems from his notebooks were published by his brother Laurence, titled *More Poems* (1936).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's *A Shropshire Lad* includes some iconic individual poems like "Loveliest of trees, the cherry now" (II), "When I was one-and-twenty" (XIII), "Is my team ploughing" (XXVII) and "Into my heart an air that kills" (XL).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His mother died on his twelfth birthday, and his father, a country solicitor, then married an elder cousin, Lucy, in 1873.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Two of his siblings became prominent writers, sister Clemence Housman and brother Laurence Housman.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman was educated at King Edward's School in Birmingham and later Bromsgrove School, where he revealed his academic promise and won prizes for his poems.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In 1877, he won an open scholarship to St John's College, Oxford, and went there to study classics.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Although introverted by nature, Housman formed strong friendships with two roommates, Moses John Jackson (1858–1923) and A.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Though Housman obtained a first in classical Moderations in 1879, his dedication to textual analysis led him to neglect the ancient history and philosophy that formed part of the Greats curriculum.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Accordingly, he failed the Finals and had to return humiliated in Michaelmas term to resit the exam so as to at least gain a lower-level pass degree.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Though some attribute Housman's unexpected performance in his exams directly to his unrequited feelings for Jackson, most biographers adduce more obvious causes.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman was indifferent to philosophy and overconfident in his exceptional gifts and he spent too much time with his friends.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He may also have been distracted by news of his father's desperate illness.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] After Oxford, Jackson went to work as a clerk in the Patent Office in London and he also arranged a job there for Housman.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The two shared a flat at 82 Talbot Road, Bayswater, with Jackson's brother Adalbert until 1885, when Housman moved to lodgings of his own, probably after Jackson responded to a declaration of love by telling Housman that he could not reciprocate his feelings.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Two years later, Jackson moved to India, placing more distance between himself and Housman.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] When he returned briefly to England in 1889 to marry, Housman was not invited to the wedding and knew nothing about it until the couple had left the country.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Adalbert Jackson died in 1892 and Housman commemorated him in a poem published as "XLII – A.J.J." of *More Poems* (1936).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Meanwhile, Housman pursued his classical studies independently, and published scholarly articles on Horace, Propertius, Ovid, Aeschylus, Euripides and Sophocles.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He also completed an edition of Propertius, which however was rejected by both Oxford University Press and Macmillan in 1885, and was destroyed after his death.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He gradually acquired such a high reputation that in 1892 he was offered and accepted the professorship of Latin at University College London (UCL).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] When, during his tenure, an immensely rare Coverdale Bible of 1535 was discovered in the UCL library and presented to the Library Committee, Housman (who had become an atheist while at Oxford) remarked that it would be better to sell it to "buy some really useful books with the proceeds".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Although Housman's early work and his responsibilities as a professor included both Latin and Greek, he began to specialise in Latin poetry.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] When asked later why he had stopped writing about Greek verse, he responded, "I found that I could not attain to excellence in both." In 1911 he took the Kennedy Professorship of Latin at Trinity College, Cambridge, where he remained for the rest of his life.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Between 1903 and 1930, Housman published his critical edition of Manilius's *Astronomicon* in five volumes.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He also edited Juvenal (1905) and Lucan (1926).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He was and may remain the last great textual critic".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In the eyes of Harry Eyres, however, Housman was "famously dry" as a professor, and his influence led to a scholarly style in the study of literature and poetry that was philological and without emotion.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Many colleagues were unnerved by Housman's scathing attacks on those he thought guilty of shoddy scholarship.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In his paper "The Application of Thought to Textual Criticism" (1921) he wrote: "A textual critic engaged upon his business is not at all like Newton investigating the motion of the planets: he is much more like a dog hunting for fleas".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He declared many of his contemporary scholars to be stupid, lazy, vain, or all three, saying: "Knowledge is good, method is good, but one thing beyond all others is necessary; and that is to have a head, not a pumpkin, on your shoulders, and brains, not pudding, in your head".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Gow, quoted examples of these attacks, noting that they "were often savage in the extreme".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Gow also related how Housman intimidated students, sometimes reducing the women to tears.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] According to Gow, Housman could never remember the names of female students, maintaining that "had he burdened his memory by the distinction between Miss Jones and Miss Robinson, he might have forgotten that between the second and fourth declension".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Among the more notable students at his Cambridge lectures was Enoch Powell, one of whose own Classical emendations was later complimented by Housman.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In his private life, Housman enjoyed country walks, gastronomy, air travel and making frequent visits to France, where he read "books which were banned in Britain as pornographic" but he struck A.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Benson, a fellow don, as being "descended from a long line of maiden aunts".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His feelings about his poetry were ambivalent and he certainly treated it as secondary to his scholarship.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He did not speak in public about his poems until 1933, when he gave a lecture "The Name and Nature of Poetry", arguing there that poetry should appeal to emotions rather than to the intellect.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His ashes are buried just outside St Laurence's Church, Ludlow.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] A cherry tree was planted there in his memory (see *A Shropshire Lad* II) and replaced by the Housman Society in 2003 with a new cherry tree nearby.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In the same vein, Harry Eyres interpreted it as "what you could see as an act of self-punishment" that so many years were devoted to "a minor Roman versifier whose long didactic poem on astrology must rank as one of the most obscure in the entire annals of poetry".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] During his years in London, Housman completed *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of 63 poems.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] After one publisher had turned it down, he helped subsidise its publication in 1896.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] At first selling slowly, it rapidly became a lasting success.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Its appeal to English musicians had helped to make it widely known before World War I, when its themes struck a powerful chord with English readers.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The book has been in print continuously since May 1896.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The poems are marked by pessimism and preoccupation with death, without religious consolation (Housman had become an atheist while still an undergraduate).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman wrote many of them while living in Highgate, London, before ever visiting Shropshire, which he presented in an idealised pastoral light as his 'land of lost content'.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman himself acknowledged that "No doubt I have been unconsciously influenced by the Greeks and Latins, but [the] chief sources of which I am conscious are Shakespeare's songs, the Scottish Border ballads, and Heine".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman began collecting a new set of poems after the First World War.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His early work was an influence on many British poets who became famous by their writing about the war, and he wrote several poems as occasional verse to commemorate the war dead.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] This included his *Epitaph on an Army of Mercenaries*, honouring the British Expeditionary Force, an elite but small force of professional soldiers sent to Belgium at the start of the war.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In the early 1920s, when Moses Jackson was dying in Canada, Housman wanted to assemble his best unpublished poems so that Jackson could read them before his death.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] These later poems, mostly written before 1910, show a greater variety of subject and form than those in *A Shropshire Lad* but lack its consistency.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He published his new collection as *Last Poems* (1922), feeling that his inspiration was exhausted and that he should not publish more in his lifetime.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] After Housman's death in 1936, his brother, Laurence published further poems in *More Poems* (1936), *A.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] E .H.: Some Poems, Some Letters and a Personal Memoir by his Brother* (1937), and *Collected Poems* (1939).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] H.* includes humorous verse such as a parody of Longfellow's poem *Excelsior*.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman also wrote a parodic *Fragment of a Greek Tragedy*, in English, first published in 1883 in *The Bromsgrovian*, the magazine of his old school, and frequently reprinted.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Sparrow himself adds, "How difficult it is to achieve a satisfactory analysis may be judged by considering the last poem in *A Shropshire Lad*.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Of its four stanzas, Housman tells us that two were 'given' him ready made; one was coaxed forth from his subconsciousness an hour or two later; the remaining one took months of conscious composition.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In 1942, Laurence Housman also deposited an essay entitled "A.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's 'De Amicitia'" in the British Library, with the proviso that it was not to be published for 25 years.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's homosexuality and his love for Moses Jackson.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Despite the conservative nature of the times and his own caution in public life, Housman was quite open in his poetry, and especially in *A Shropshire Lad*, about his deeper sympathies.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Poem XXX of that sequence, for instance, speaks of how "Fear contended with desire": "Others, I am not the first, / Have willed more mischief than they durst".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His poem "Oh who is that young sinner with the handcuffs on his wrists?", written after the trial of Oscar Wilde, addressed more general attitudes towards homosexuals.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] This refers to an old paraphrasing for homosexuality in English law.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry, especially *A Shropshire Lad*, was set to music by many British, and in particular English, composers in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The national, pastoral and traditional elements of his style resonated with similar trends in English music.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In 1904, the cycle *A Shropshire Lad* was set by Arthur Somervell, who in 1898 had begun to develop the concept of the English song-cycle in his version of Tennyson's "Maud".
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Stephen Banfield believes it was acquaintance with Somervell's cycle that led other composers to set Housman: Ralph Vaughan Williams is likely to have attended the first performance at the Aeolian Hall on 3 February 1905.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] His well-known cycle of six songs *On Wenlock Edge*, for string quartet, tenor and piano, was published in 1909.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Between 1909 and 1911, George Butterworth produced settings in two collections, *Six Songs from A Shropshire Lad* and *Bredon Hill and Other Songs*.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He also wrote the orchestral tone poem *A Shropshire Lad*, first performed at Leeds Festival in 1912.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Ivor Gurney was another composer who made renowned settings of Housman's poems.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Towards the end of World War I, he was working on his cycle *Ludlow and Teme*, for voice and string quartet (published in 1919), and went on to compose the eight-song cycle *The Western Playland* in 1921.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] One more who set Housman songs during this period was John Ireland in the song cycle, *The Land of Lost Content* (1920–21).
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Charles Wilfred Orr produced 24 Housman settings in songs and song cycles composed from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Even composers not directly associated with the 'pastoral' tradition, such as Arnold Bax, Lennox Berkeley and Arthur Bliss, were attracted to Housman's poetry.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Housman's attitude to musical interpretations of his poetry, and indeed to music in general, was either indifference or torment.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] He told his friend Percy Withers that he knew nothing of music and it meant nothing to him.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Withers once played him a record of the Vaughan Williams setting, but realised he had made a mistake when he saw the look of disgust on the poet's face.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Nevertheless, by 1976, a catalogue listed 400 musical settings of Housman's poems.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] As of 2024, Lieder Net Archive records 678 settings of 188 texts.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The earliest commemoration of Housman was in the chapel of Trinity College in Cambridge, where there is a memorial brass on the south wall.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The Latin inscription was composed by his colleague there, A.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Gow, who was also the author of a biographical and bibliographical sketch published immediately following his death.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] From 1947, University College London's academic common room was dedicated to his memory as the Housman Room.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Blue plaques followed later elsewhere, the first being on Byron Cottage in Highgate in 1969, recording the fact that *A Shropshire Lad* was written there.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] More followed, placed on his Worcestershire birthplace, his homes and school in Bromsgrove.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The latter were encouraged by the Housman Society, which was founded in the town in 1973.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Another initiative was the statue in Bromsgrove High Street, showing the poet striding with walking stick in hand.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The work of local sculptor Kenneth Potts, it was unveiled on 22 March 1985.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The blue plaques in Worcestershire were set up on the centenary of *A Shropshire Lad* in 1996.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] In September of the same year, a memorial window lozenge was dedicated at Poets' Corner in Westminster Abbey.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The following year saw the première of Tom Stoppard's play *The Invention of Love*, whose subject is the relationship between Housman and Moses Jackson.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] As the 150th anniversary of his birth approached, London University inaugurated its Housman lectures on classical subjects in 2005, initially given every second year then annually after 2011.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] The anniversary itself in 2009 saw the publication of a new edition of *A Shropshire Lad*, including pictures from across Shropshire taken by local photographer Gareth Thomas.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] Among other events, there were performances of Vaughan Williams's *On Wenlock Edge* and Ivor Gurney's *Ludlow and Teme* at St Laurence's Church in Ludlow.
[src:river-severn/a-e-housman] These lectures are listed by date of delivery, with date of first publication given separately if different.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The **A38**, parts of which are known as Devon Expressway, Bristol Road and Gloucester Road, is a major A-class trunk road in England.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road runs from Bodmin in Cornwall to Mansfield in Nottinghamshire.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It is 292 miles (470 km) long, making it the longest two digit A road in England.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It was formerly known as the *Leeds–Exeter Trunk Road*, when this description also included the A61.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Before the opening of the M5 motorway in the 1960s and 1970s, the A38 formed the main "holiday route" from the Midlands to Somerset, Devon and Cornwall.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Considerable lengths of the road in the West Midlands closely follow Roman roads, including part of Icknield Street.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Between Worcester and Birmingham the current A38 follows the line of a Saxon salt road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] For most of the length of the M5 motorway, the A38 road runs alongside it as a single carriageway road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road starts on the eastern side of Bodmin at a junction with the A30 before traversing the edge of the town to meet the A30 again.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It travels through the picturesque Glynn Valley to Dobwalls and Liskeard, which are bypassed by a dual carriageway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Dobwalls section contains a bat bridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 continues through the Cornish countryside, bypassing the centre of Saltash and continuing through the Saltash Tunnel.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Immediately after the tunnel the River Tamar is crossed using the Tamar Bridge where the route resumes dual carriageway status.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The section from Plymouth to Exeter is known locally as the Devon Expressway; it forms the southern border of Dartmoor National Park, and serves as a southward extension of the M5 motorway opening in 1977.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It is 42 miles (68 km) long and was completed in the early 1970s.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] There are several grade separated junctions along its length mainly for local traffic; including a three-level stacked roundabout interchange for the A386, which heads out towards Dartmoor National Park.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The route was reserved for the Parkway as early as 1943, when it was included in the Plan for Plymouth.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In the early 1990s, the Marsh Mills junction was significantly remodelled, reducing the size of the roundabout and building a flyover over the top of it, allowing free flowing access from the Plympton bypass onto the Parkway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The viaducts carrying the A38 over the River Plym, which after the construction of the Marsh Mills flyover became the Exeter bound sliproads, were built in 1969–70 as part of the Plympton bypass.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] They were replaced in the 1990s due to suffering from Alkali Silica Reaction, and the project, completed in February 1996 at a cost of £12.25 million, involved the world's largest sideways bridge slide at the time for the 410 metres (1,350 ft), 5,500 tonne bridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This required the road to be closed for only 48 hours, which won it an AA National Motoring Award in 1996 for innovation and minimisation of traffic congestion.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road widens to a three-lane dual carriageway for the Plympton bypass.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This opened in 1971 and was the first section of the Devon Expressway to be built on a new alignment, as well as being the first sizeable dual carriageway section of the route.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Before Ivybridge, the route roughly parallels the original route, bypassing the village of Lee Mill which is now home to a large trading estate.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Ivybridge bypass opened in 1973 and the South Brent bypass in 1974, both on new alignments.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 passes Endsleigh Garden Centre, which used to have direct access from the dual carriageway, although since the early 2000s this has been closed and the garden centre is accessed from the Westover junction for Ivybridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The route originally ended at the Marsh Mills roundabout, which when opened was the largest in Europe.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The section of the A38 between the A382 junction and Ashburton was built on a new alignment parallel to the old road, and was opened in 1974.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Trago Mills, a locally well known retailer, is passed by the road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Ashburton bypass, much like the Kennford bypass, uses the alignment of a much older 1930s single carriageway bypass, which was subsequently upgraded to dual carriageway by 1974.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At the town of Buckfastleigh, the route once again bypasses on a new alignment, although due to the challenging topography of the area, the road crosses part of the town on a viaduct.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road occupies part of the alignment of the former Totnes to Ashburton railway line.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Buckfastleigh to the A385 junction, the current road follows the route of original single carriageway, with the majority of this section being upgraded between 1973 and 1974, although a small section at Dean Prior was upgraded between 1966 and 1967.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This section is of a poor quality when compared to the majority of the route between Exeter and Plymouth, containing several side turnings with short exit/entry slips, and properties which back onto the road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The town of Chudleigh and the village of Chudleigh Knighton are bypassed on a new alignment, which opened in 1973, and the following section at Heathfield up to the A382 junction was upgraded from the original route between 1966 and 1968.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Some of this section follows part of the old Teign Valley Line railway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Before Kennford, the route splits, with the A38 heading for Plymouth and the A380 heading towards Torbay.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The third lane is lost at the top of the hill, and the next section, the Harcombe bends is an original dual carriageway section, older than the rest of the route and this is evident with its sharp bends.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Devon Expressway ends near the village of Kennford, south of Exeter, at the terminus of the M5.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This initial section was opened in 1977, along with the remaining section of the M5, and is a three-lane dual carriageway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The village of Kennford is bypassed, on an alignment of a 1930s bypass, which was upgraded to a dual-carriageway in the 1960s and then widened to a dual three-lane road in 1975.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A junction to the south of Exeter represents a third meeting point of the A38 with the A30, from which point the A38 multiplexes with the M5 before re-emerging from junction 27 near Waterloo Cross, 21 miles (34 km) north of Exeter.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From junction 27 the A38 heads north via Wellington, Taunton, Bridgwater, Highbridge and Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Waterloo Cross to Birmingham, the road is paralleled by the M5, where the A38 has reverted to taking local traffic only.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Bristol, it continues north via Gloucester, Tewkesbury, Worcester and Bromsgrove to Birmingham.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Between Worcester and Birmingham the A38 followed the line of an identified Saxon Salt road, one of six leading out of Droitwich.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At Bromsgrove, it meets the M42 and the B4096 at junction 1 at Lickey End.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It passes through Upper Catshill and meets the M5 at junction 4 (along with the A491 road) near Lydiate Ash.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From here to Edgbaston, the road is mostly dual carriageway, single-lane sections having been replaced in the first decade of the 21st century (see history section, below).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Following completion of the Selly Oak bypass, the A38 deviates from its original route and briefly multiplexes with the A4040 outer Ring Road before forming the new bypass which is controversially named New Fosse Way.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] (The old route is designated B384 having been briefly B38).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In the centre of Birmingham, a section of the road becomes the Aston Expressway A38(M) motorway, running from the north-eastern side of the Inner Ring Road through Aston to the junction with the M6 motorway at Gravelly Hill Interchange, better known as *Spaghetti Junction*.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The West Midlands section of the A38 is one of the areas chosen by the Highways Agency to monitor the effectiveness of driver location signs in assisting motorists to communicate their location to the emergency services.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Birmingham the road bypasses Sutton Coldfield and Lichfield, before taking up the route of the Roman road, Ryknild Street, (also spelt *Icknield* or *Rykneld*), as far as Derby.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At Wychnor, the road crosses the River Trent and enters the district of East Staffordshire.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At Barton Turn, near the B5016 junction, the road runs right alongside the Cross Country Route for around 1 mile (1.6 km).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This railway line follows the line of the A38 from Derby to Plymouth.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Alrewas to Burton, the path called The Way for the Millennium follows the northbound carriageway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Clay Mills, the road passes through the district of South Derbyshire, passing the grade separated junction with the A5132 for Willington.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Near Burnaston, there is a three-level stacked roundabout interchange with the A50; this junction features Derby with Burton services.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road enters the City of Derby borough 0.5 miles (0.8 km) north of the Littleover interchange.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] For nearly 4 miles (6.4 km), the A38 forms part of Derby's outer ring road, including three roundabouts: Kingsway (or *Grand Canyon*) for the A5111; Markeaton for the A52; and Little Eaton (or *Abbey Hill*) for the A61 and B6179.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The section of road between Kingsway roundabout to just north of Markeaton is urban in nature and thus subject to a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Originally terminating in Derby at the junction of *Babington Lane* with *St Peter's Street* (formerly the A6), the road enters the district of Amber Valley where it passes Drum Hill just north of Little Eaton and is crossed at this point by the Midshires Way and Centenary Way.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] There is a junction for the B6179 to Ripley and Belper.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At Alfreton, there is a grade separated junction with the A61, A615 and B6179.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The section from Alfreton to the M1, the Alfreton–South Normanton Bypass, opened as the A615 in the late 1960s.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This section has a grade separated junction with the B600 for Somercotes and the Cotes Park industrial estate, and where it crosses the Nottingham spur of the Midland Main Line it enters the district of Bolsover.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] As a 1970s upgrade to the route of the A61 north of Derby (which became the B6179), the A38 bypasses Ripley passing through former opencast mining land, before joining end-on with the former A615 Alfreton bypass at Watchorn Intersection.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Into Nottinghamshire, the road bypasses Sutton-in-Ashfield, dropping to a single carriageway configuration of 1980s construction, including multiple traffic light controlled junctions – such as the Mansfield, Ashfield Regeneration Route ("MARR").
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The final section of the A38 from Sutton, past King's Mill Hospital into Mansfield, is purely urban in nature and is single carriageway, joining the A6009 in Mansfield Town Centre at the end of the route from Cornwall to the northern Midlands.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] When first designated in 1922, the A38 ran from the centre of Plymouth to Derby.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It was later extended west from Plymouth on the former route of the A389 over the Torpoint Ferry to a junction with the A30 at Bodmin.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] When the Tamar Bridge was opened in 1961, the A38 was rerouted on the former line of the A374, through Tideford, over the new bridge and through Crownhill, joining the old route at Plympton.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The old route of the A38, via Torpoint and the centre of Plymouth, was redesignated the A374.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 was extended north from Derby to the M1 motorway and Mansfield in 1977, partly on the former line of the A615.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Liskeard bypass, stretching for 6 miles (10 km) from the west of Liskeard to Trerulefoot, opened in June 1976.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A public inquiry was held for the Dobwalls bypass in February 2005, which was expected to cost £32 million.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The bottleneck was removed when the bypass, linking the existing Liskeard bypass to the current single carriageway section through the Glynn Valley opened in the Winter of 2008.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A campaign to open this road was started by villagers in Dobwalls in 1930, but planning for building the road was not granted until 2006, the work starting on 15 November that year.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Two bat bridges and one bat house were added as the road cut through existing bat flight lines.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] After opening the Dobwall bypass experienced problems with surface water.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This led to lane closures in winter due to risk of ice.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A major scheme to reconstruct a mile of the bypass started in September 2014 and is expected to last until May 2015.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It is thought it will cost an extra £10.6 million.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In a separate improvement within the Glynn Valley, the Highways Agency stabilised a 840-metre (0.52 mi) section of the road near Bodmin Parkway railway station.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The work, which commenced in October 2007, was carried out to shore up the verge, which had been built on an embankment supported by dry stone walling and the root systems of large trees.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It was completed in May 2008 seeing the installation of kerbing, road drainage gulleys, safety barriers as well as increasing the verge width to allow for a new surface water drainage system.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 in Devon runs between Tamar Bridge outside Plymouth and junction 31 of the M5, where the motorway ends; this section is known as the **Devon Expressway**.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It is mainly a two-lane dual carriageway which runs between Exeter and Plymouth serving as a continuation of the M5 motorway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It is a popular route for tourists travelling to Cornwall, though those wanting to use a continuous dual carriageway route to Cornwall can use the A30 rather than using the Devon Expressway before joining the less major roads over the border in Cornwall.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It then runs concurrently with the M5 until junction 27, where it splits and enters Somerset independent but parallel to the M5.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] During the mid-1960s, small sections of the route between Plymouth and Exeter were upgraded to dual carriageway, such as those at Dean Prior and Heathfield.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This was followed by the construction of Plympton bypass in 1970–71, with the majority of realignment, such as the Ivybridge and Buckfastleigh bypasses, being completed during 1973–74.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The route, now known as the Devon Expressway, was largely complete by 1975, with the final section between Kennford and the M5 opening in 1977, coinciding with the completion of the final section of the M5 around Exeter during the same year.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Whilst many of the sections were newly constructed realignments, some sections such as the Ashburton and Kennford bypasses were upgraded from the original 1930s single carriageway bypasses.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Parkway, the section of dual carriageway through the suburbs of Plymouth between the Tamar Bridge and Marsh Mills, was constructed in 1983–84, along a route which had been reserved for this road since 1943.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This was followed by the construction of a flyover over Marsh Mills roundabout in 1992, providing a non-stop route between the Plympton bypass and the Parkway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Plympton bypass opened in 1971, and was used for a stage in the 1974 Tour de France, with a 3.5 miles (5.6 km) stretch closed to traffic in order to allow the visit of the race to the United Kingdom.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The viaducts carrying the A38 over the River Plym, which after the construction of the Marsh Mills flyover became the Exeter bound sliproads, were built in 1969–1970 as part of the Plympton bypass.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] They were replaced in the 1990s due to suffering from Alkali Silica Reaction, and the project, completed in February 1996 at a cost of £12.25million, involved the world's largest sideways bridge slide at the time for the 410 metres (1,350 ft), 5,500 tonne bridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This required the road to be closed for only 48 hours, winning it an AA National Motoring Award in 1996 for innovation and minimisation of traffic congestion.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] As with any major road, accidents are likely to occur; however due to the substandard design of some sections of the route between Exeter and Plymouth, the accident rate has been identified as being above the national average for the type of road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A spate of accidents in April 2009 heightened local awareness of the issue, with local MP Gary Streeter calling for a review of the road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A number of improvements have been made along the route in recent years, mainly being the replacement of worn-out road surfaces, such as those at Buckfastleigh and Ivybridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] These projects have also included the replacement of signage, and the reconstruction of exit/entry slips for side turnings, in a bid to make the road safer.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Presently, the route between Plymouth and the end of M5 is all dual carriageway, and branded the Devon Expressway, being the primary route that links Plymouth to the rest of the country.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond the end of the M5, the road runs concurrently with and as the M5 until junction 27.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From junction 27 of the M5 to East Brent, the A38 runs broadly parallel to the motorway: junctions 22 to 27 are mostly spurs connecting to the road and all no further than 1.5 miles (2.4 km) from it.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 runs around Wellington, through the county seat of Taunton, North Petherton and Highbridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond Highbridge and junction 22, the road departs the motorway and resumes primary status, going through Winscombe, Churchill and Lower Langford where it crosses the A368 between Weston-super-Mare and Bath.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This route is the suggested route for accessing the south of Bristol and Bristol Airport from the South West.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The centre of Bridgwater was a notorious bottleneck on the "holiday route" as traffic from both the A38 and the A39 had to negotiate through the town centre in order to cross the River Parrett.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The construction of a new reinforced concrete road bridge, the Blake Bridge, which opened in March 1958 as part of a southern bypass took much of the traffic away from the centre of Bridgwater.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The opening of the M5 in 1974 further reduced the traffic pressure.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This is complemented by a link road (Western Way) linking the A38 and the A39 north and west of the town respectively.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Much of the A38 through Somerset was built as single carriageway, with some three-lane passing points.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] However, the construction of the M5 through Somerset, in the early 1970s, led to the building of links between the A38 and the M5 in the form of new roundabouts on the A38 linking into adjacent junctions on the M5.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 serves Bristol Airport to the southwest of the city, and enters the city itself at Highridge, along Bedminster Down and into Bedminster.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It runs through central Bristol before leaving northwards along North Street, Stokes Croft and Gloucester Road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It runs past the former Filton Airport in South Gloucestershire to meet the M5 again at junction 16.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Thereafter it runs through Almondsbury and by-passes Thornbury to enter Gloucestershire.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] South of Bristol, the road was diverted in 2001 to cater for an extension of the runway and installation of a category 3 landing system at Bristol Airport.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The route south of the city, despite serving the airport, is single-carriageway and suffers from heavy volume of traffic at peak times, and congestion along Bedminster Down.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Bedminster Down the A38 follows West Street and East Street through the centre of Bedminster, but drivers from the south were advised by road signs not to follow the A38 into the city, but to use the A3029 (Winterstoke Road) to enter from the west, as this route had a greater capacity.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] As part of the *Greater Bristol Strategic Transport Study*, a link road had been under consideration to the south of Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This is in part due to the congestion at Winterstoke Road and Barrow Gurney, both of which are very busy, especially the latter where the road can only accommodate travelling at one direction at a given time; and the incomplete Bristol Ring Road (A4174).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This road, named the South Bristol Link, was subsequently opened in 2017 and now surpasses the A3029 (Winterstoke Road) as the main route from Bristol Airport to the city centre and the motorway network north of Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In central Bristol, the original route from Bedminster Bridge ran up Redcliffe Hill and then along Redcliff Street to Bristol Bridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In the 1950s Redcliff Street was declassified, following completion of the Inner Circuit Road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It then follows Rupert Street to the St James Barton roundabout and Stokes Croft.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The route to the north of the city is also very busy: it runs as a single carriageway up to the junction with the A4174 ring road at Filton, and where it runs as Gloucester Road is a busy shopping parade.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond the ring road, it runs as dual-carriageway past the site of the now-closed Filton Airport which lies in South Gloucestershire, which contains bases for Royal Mail, Airbus, Rolls-Royce and others.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Almondsbury Junction to Southmead Roundabout Improvement would cost £4,915,000 for 3 miles (4.8 km) of dual cariageway in 1975.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This improvement was first announced in April 1968, along with the M5 extension from Edithmead to Exeter, and the extension of the M32.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It opened in parts, with the last part on 31 August 1978 It was built by Sir Lindsay Parkinson & Company.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond junction 16 of the M5 it runs as a broad single carriageway, again parallel to the M5 in route towards Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The present road from Bristol through Horfield was one of the additional roads added to the Bristol turnpike roads in 1749.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This passed through Thornbury to Stone, just beyond the boundary of South Gloucestershire, where it met one of the Gloucester turnpike roads.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Almondsbury, the road approximately follows the line of the Roman road from Sea Mills to Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The previous main route out of Bristol (one of twelve roads from the city, turnpiked in 1727) was Stapleton and Hambrook to the upper end of Tytherington and thence to Stone.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This seems to be parts of B4058, B4424, and then unclassified roads.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] However, Ogilby's *Britannia* shows a route following the B4058 as far as Cromhall, then through Stinchcombe Bottom, Dursley, and Cam before joining the present road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Bristol turnpike roads were continued by a turnpike road established in 1727, described as "from the City of Gloucester to the village of Stone being the great road from the north to west of this kingdom".
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Much of the road, follows a Roman road, but deviates from it between Buckover and Whitfield.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 was rerouted along the Gloucester Bypass when it was built, and the old route through the city became the A430.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In 2007 the Gloucester South Western Bypass opened to traffic, costing £43 million.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Though it is numbered A430 and not technically part of the A38, traffic wishing to continue on the A38 on the other side of the city is signed to use the bypass, rather than the existing A38.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond Gloucester, the A38 was probably only improved in 1756 under an Act (29 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 58) dealing with roads from that city towards Cheltenham and Tewkesbury.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The next section (from Coombe Hill) was improved as one of the Tewkesbury roads, again from 1727.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Act refers to this as the Upper Way to Gloucester in contrast to the Lower Way, which went via Wainsload Bridge.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] When this Act was renewed in 1756, the road from Tewkesbury to a farmhouse called the Old Blue Ball (now Bluebell Farm) was also included.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This was in Earls Croome, Worcestershire, and was where one of the Worcester turnpikes ended.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Much of this stretch of the road originated as a Roman road, but the later road left the Roman line near Naunton in Ripple.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The name Stratford Bridge on the county boundary confirms its Roman origin there.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 into Tewkesbury has been diverted away from the now declassified Gloucester Road along a new link road to the A438 east of the town centre.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The A38 resumes in Tewkesbury town centre where the A438 has always met the A38 near the Abbey.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The current A38 road follows from the southern end of one of the Worcester turnpike trust's roads which was originally set in 1726, by the Worcester Roads Act 1725 (12 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 14), at Severn Stoke, but an act of Parliament of 1737, the Worcester Roads Act 1736 (10 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 5), extended it to Upton Bridge (taking it past Bluebell Farm).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] North of the city, the road was a particularly important one as it connected the saltmaking centre of Droitwich with the River Severn.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In 1706, this was described as heavily used for the 'carriage of salt, iron, coals and other wares'.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] When it was renewed by the Worcester to Droitwich Road Act 1725 (12 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 20), it was extended from the Tything of Whistons to the Lower Slip of the Quay of Worcester; from Droitwich to Dyers Bridge (M5 junction 5) near Bromsgrove; and through the town of Droitwich from "Netherwith" [Netherwich] Bridge to a place called "Chapel on the Bridge".
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In 1749, this was again extended, by the Worcestershire Roads Act 1748 (22 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 43), through the town of Bromsgrove to Spadebourne Bridge, immediately north of the town.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Where the road leaves Worcester, it again does not follow the line of the Roman road in the same direction until it picks up the Roman line, just south of Martin Hussingtree.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Roman road took a more direct line over Rainbow Hill and through Blackpole, now B4550.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] From Martin Hussingtree, the A38 closely follows the Roman line to beyond Bromsgrove.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The present road deviates from its line when it was originally classified at Droitwich where the main road is a bypass, the old road now mostly being B4090.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This happens again at Bromsgrove, where A38 is again a bypass, the old line mostly now being B4091 and Bromsgrove High Street (now partly pedestrianised, then through the town centre.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Bromsgrove Eastern Bypass was constructed in 1980.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] A short distance north of where the old A38 (now declassified) joins the Bromsgrove bypass, is Lickey End, where an old highway intersection has been replaced by junction 1 of M42 motorway.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Here, the road is joined from the southeast by the B4096, Alcester Road, which was from 1754 one of the roads of the Alcester turnpike trust.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The continuation northwards of B4096 is called Old Birmingham Road, because it was the original route of the turnpike to Birmingham, climbing to a pass in the Lickey Hills.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Roman road also went through the same pass, but its route to the pass was probably rather straighter.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond the motorway junction, the A38 was turnpiked, not as the turnpike to Birmingham, but to Halesowen and Dudley, by the Bromsgrove and Birmingham Roads Act 1726 (13 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 15) that also turnpiked Old Birmingham Road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Worcester and Warwick Roads Act 1741 (15 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 7) appointed separate trustees for the Dudley Road in 1742 and the Bromsgrove to Birmingham Roads Act 1747 (21 Geo.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] 22) appointed trustees for the Birmingham Road in 1748.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road continues from the M42 junction 1 towards Catshill and up a short incline at which there is a fork.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Prior to the construction of the M5 motorway in the early 1960s, the Halesowen Road continued West whilst Birmingham Road continued North to meet the existing dual carriageway just South of Rubery.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] After the M5 was constructed, all traffic was diverted along Halesowen Road (then the A459) which was widened and lit to provide a direct route for the A38 to meet the M5 at junction 4 at Lydiate Ash, with the dual carriageway continuing North to Rubery.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The original Birmingham Road survives to this day, but is noticeably lightly trafficked due to its cul-de-sac nature.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Its considerable width makes it a very popular route for learner drivers and as such is affectionately named by local people as "Learners Mile".
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road from Lydiate Ash to Longbridge was laid out as a new road in the early 1960s to collaborate with the construction of the M5 motorway which opened in 1962.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road passed through the centre of Rubery until the £770,000 (£13 million in 2025), Rubery Bypass opened in December 1965.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Lydiate Ash was the northern end of the M5 for many years in the 1960s, with traffic transferring onto the A38, which was diverted at this point to link with the M5.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] At Longbridge, new turnpike joined the Roman road and the original turnpike, and runs straight towards the city centre.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Northfield bypass, taking traffic away from the congested town centre opened on 11 April 2007.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Between Northfield and Selly Oak, the road is likely to have been in use in the medieval period as the road approximately follows the boundary of the former Weoley Park, the great park belonging to Weoley Castle.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This required new bridges to carry the Worcester and Birmingham Canal and the Cross-City railway line over the road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The destination of the Roman road was clearly Metchley Fort, but A38 turns away towards the city centre.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] After Selly Oak, the A38 takes the Bristol Road into the city as far as the Belgrave Interchange with the A4540 Middleway ring road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The city centre section takes a novel line, laid out as part of extensive reconstruction works in the 1960s, and is one of the few remaining pieces of the original "concrete collar" inner ring road.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The old road took a largely similar line as far as what is now Paradise Circus, before zig-zagging in a less direct and much slower route through the city centre, taking in the north side of New Street Station and then travelling along Corporation street to briefly rejoin its modern alignment.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This merges directly onto the M6 in both directions, as well as the A5127 and A38 surface streets, via an intertwined series of flyovers, meaning there is an uninterrupted run from the motorway and these suburban feeder roads all the way to the southern ring road junction.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond Salford Circus, the A38 used to pass through Erdington, Wylde Green and particularly Sutton Coldfield town centres (and then Four Oaks, Mere Green and Shenstone) on its way towards Lichfield, before the extensive Sutton Coldfield Bypass was built.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This passes far to the east of its namesake town, as well as many other north Birmingham suburbs from Erdington through to Four Oaks, requiring an extensive diversion and use of redesignated link roads to access.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The bypass is two-lane dual carriageway throughout, offers a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit from Salford to Minworth, and is national speed limit (70 mph (110 km/h) for light vehicles) for most of the rest of its run.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In Erdington and Sutton Coldfield, the original A5127 has been bypassed a second time by more minor urban relief roads, easing congestion in and allowing partial pedestrianisation of their respective town centre shopping areas.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Historically, it is not clear which turnpike trust was responsible for the section of road from Birmingham to Lichfield, or even whether it *was* a turnpike.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Also, the A5127 out of Sutton picks up the Roman road route a little north of Mere Green (having itself diverted via Metchley Fort, the modern suburbs of Perry Barr and Kingstanding, then Sutton Park and Four Oaks/Little Aston), and follows it to Lichfield.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road (now A5127) from the county boundary at Shenstone Woodend, through Shenstone to Lichfield was one of the roads of the Lichfield Turnpike Trust, established in 1729.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] However, this section of the old A38 has been replaced by new dual carriageways.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond Lichfield, the old A38 (now A5127) joins the Roman Ryknild Street at Streethay and immediately after that A5127 joins the present A38.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Ryknild Street had to that point run roughly parallel to A38, but following a different line from Metchley through Wall, its line sometimes being used by modern roads (including B4138).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The section from Lichfield to Alrewas was dualled in 1958.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The £500,000 (£9.33 million in 2025), section from Alrewas to Wychnor Farm near Wychnor Hall, and the £150,000 (£2.8 million in 2025),section from Wychnor Farm to Barton Turn both opened in 1962.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This long stretch of road closely follows Ryknild Street (whose destination was the Roman fort at Little Chester) until just short of Branston where A38 swings west, perhaps to avoid low ground.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The Roman road is used by minor roads through the suburbs of Burton upon Trent and then A5121 to rejoin the present A38 beyond the river Dove near Clay Mills.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road from Lichfield to Burton upon Trent was another of the roads maintained by the Lichfield Turnpike Trust from 1729.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This diverged from the present line at Branston, taking the road through the town centre, and is now classified as A5121.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The road from Burton to Derby was turnpiked in 1753.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Beyond the start of the Derby bypass, the old A38 has been reclassified as A5250.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] This follows Ryknild Street as far as Littleover.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] In March 1969, the 'Allestree Link Road', from the A6 at Allestree to the former A61 was opened, crossing the River Derwent and Midland Main Line.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Further improvements in the late 1960s and 1970s saw construction of the £5.2 million (£40.4 million in 2025) Mickleover bypass to the south-west of Derby opened on 19 February 1975.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] Although the government had approved the section through Allestree as early as 1974, before the Mickleover bypass had been completed, this section had many objections from nearby residents, delaying its construction (from the A52 to the A6).
[src:river-severn/a38-road] It was opposed directly by Derby Borough Council and the former Derby Higher Education College.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The £17 million (£57.8 million in 2025) road was eventually opened on 7 September 1983, known as *Queensway*.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] An extension of the A38 northwards, crossing the M1 at junction 28, and ending in Mansfield was built.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The £3 million (£17.6 million in 2025) Little Eaton-Holbrook Improvement opened on 3 October 1977.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The £12 million (£70.5 million in 2025) 10-mile (16 km) Ripley-Swanwick Bypass was opened by Eric Varley (MP for Chesterfield) on 21 October 1977, although the section from Alfreton to the Hartshay Hill roundabout with the A610 had been open to traffic since 5 September 1977.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] To the east of junction 28 of the M1, the road used to be the A615 until October 1977.
[src:river-severn/a38-road] The alignment of this road is relatively modern as the dangerous junction with Berristow Lane was improved to grade-separated in the late 1990s, incorporating access to a busy shopping centre.
[src:river-severn/a4025-road-p01] List of A roads in zone 4 in Great Britain starting north of the A4 and south/west of the A5 (roads beginning with 4).
[src:river-severn/a4025-road-p01] Only roads that have individual articles have been linked in the "Road" column below.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The **M32** is a 4.4-mile-long (7.1 km) motorway in South Gloucestershire and Bristol, England.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] It provides a link from the M4, a major motorway linking London and South Wales, to Bristol city centre and is maintained by National Highways, the national roads body.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The motorway was planned concurrently with the M4 in the 1960s, and construction was complete to Eastville in northeast Bristol by 1970.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The southernmost section was delayed by engineering challenges and industrial action, and did not open until 1975.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Since the mid-2000s, there have been plans to use the M32 as part of a park and ride facility which would reduce congestion in Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Though the M32 has a small traffic flow, it is one of the most congested motorways in the region as it connects a number of key areas.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] As well as providing one of the few high-quality routes into the centre of Bristol, it is the only significant link from the M4 to the A4174 Bristol Ring Road.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Parts of the M32 are reaching the end of their intended lifespan, leading to reduced speed limits and occasional closures for remedial work.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Local residents have criticised the M32, complaining that it has severed communities and has an unacceptable noise level.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Its northern end is at junction 19 of the M4, near Winterbourne Down.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Originally a grade separated roundabout junction, it was modified in 1992 to remove conflicting traffic movements in order to increase capacity.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The motorway then runs south between Filton in the west and Frenchay in the east.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] After meeting the A4174 ring road at junction 1, it crosses the boundary from South Gloucestershire to Bristol, passing to the east of Horfield, Lockleaze and Easton.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Junction 2, next to Eastville Park, meets the B4469 providing access to Horfield.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Midway through, a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit begins.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The motorway continues further south and ends just beyond junction 3, north of St Paul's.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] A dual carriageway continues as the **A4032** into the centre of Bristol, with a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The tower of St Agnes Church, adjacent to the M32 near junction 3, is a local landmark visible to motorists entering the city.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The M32 is a trunk road, therefore its maintenance and upkeep is paid for by National Highways, the national roads authority.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Most of the road has two lanes in each direction, though an extended sliproad north of junction 2 provides a climbing lane, and the short section between junction 1 and the M4 has three lanes both ways.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The M32 was planned to be a key radial link through to the hub of a network of radial and ring roads within a rectangle encompassing Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Other bounds of this scheme were parts of the M4 (north eastern side), the M5 (north western side) and the tidal reaches of the River Avon (south western side), the south eastern side not being defined by landmarks.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The motorway was partly funded by Gloucestershire County Council and Bristol City Council, with a 75 per cent grant supplied by the national Ministry of Transport.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] It was provisionally called the Hambrook Spur or the Bristol Parkway during construction, and was built in three distinct stages between 1966 and 1975.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The first section, from the M4 to junction 1, opened concurrently with that motorway in September 1966.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The second section, through to junction 2, was a co-operative design between the Gloucestershire county surveyor and the design consultants Freeman Fox & Partners.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Construction was awarded to Sir Robert McAlpine, who began work in June 1968.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The northern section was designed as a full-speed (70 mph (110 km/h)) motorway as far as Eastville, after which the motorway ran on an elevated section with a lower design standard.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] This section was opened by the Secretary of State for Transport, John Peyton in July 1970.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The total cost was £3 million (now £41 million).
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 1972, a polystyrene storage depot on Muller Road near junction 2 caught fire, leading to the closure of the southbound M32 for six days.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The third section was the most technically demanding, as it ran through heavily built-up urban areas and required numerous properties to be demolished, along with the 665-foot (203 m) "Thirteen-arch viaduct" near Stapleton Road that was built in 1874.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Work was delayed owing to the Three-Day Week industrial action in 1974, and further because of a national builders' strike.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] During construction, the Local Government Act 1972 was passed, and responsibility passed to the newly created Avon County Council in April 1974.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] This section, and hence the full extent of the motorway, was opened to traffic in May 1975.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The cost was reported to be £10.4 million (now £70 million).
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] A bus lane, constructed in 2008 on the southbound carriageway of the A4032, Newfoundland Way, links the end of the M32 at junction 3 with Cabot Circus.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] It starts just north of junction 3 and runs for around 1,000 m (1,100 yards), adjacent to the central reservation, and becomes a general running lane for its final 165 yards (151 m) to a signal controlled junction.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The hard shoulder and the remaining width of carriageway were rebuilt as two narrowed running lanes for general traffic, and the speed limit was reduced to 30 mph (48 km/h).
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2009, the council announced that a park and ride facility would be developed next to the M32 to help alleviate congestion in the city centre.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The project was expected to create 1,500 parking spaces and cost £191 million.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2015, construction began on a bus-only junction between junctions 1 and 2, on land partly allocated to the Stapleton Allotments and near the Stoke Park estate.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The project is part of the North Fringe to Hengrove MetroBus rapid transit route package, and involves creating new slip roads, a connecting route to Stoke Lane and a new bridge over the M32 to be completed by mid-2016.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The bridge was lifted into place in June, which required closing the M32 to all traffic.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Despite this, the M32 is frequently congested as it is a popular route into the centre of Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] During the morning rush hour, queues can tail back onto the motorway from the city centre.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2014, the Highways Agency reported that the M32 between junctions 1 and 2 was the most unreliable motorway journey along the entire M4 corridor between London and South Wales, with over 56 per cent of journeys taking longer than predicted.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The problem is exacerbated whenever there is an incident on the M4 around Bristol, as drivers attempt to use the M32 as a diversion route, creating further traffic and congestion.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The M32 forms a bottleneck at its northern end as it is the only link between the M4 and the A4174 Bristol Ring Road.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2015, Chris Skidmore, Member of Parliament for Kingswood, launched the Gateway2Growth campaign, which would see a new road running from the M4 at Emersons Green to the A4174.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Highways England were concerned that the M32, especially its elevated sections, will reach its planned end-of-life around 2020.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Urgent works were recommended on the Eastville Viaduct in particular, which had deficient surfacing, barriers and lighting.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] A 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit was placed along the viaduct, while surveying work was carried out in 2016 during the Metrobus junction refurbishments.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The M32 has been criticised for severing longstanding links in Bristol.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Older residents have claimed that formerly close-knit communities such as Easton have been shut off by the imposing concrete barriers next to the motorway.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] It has been criticised for running through the grounds of Stoke Park, spoiling the local atmosphere and requiring part of the estate including the Duchess Pond to be demolished.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2008, Jeremy Isaacs claimed the motorway was a reason that Bristol did not win the European Capital of Culture award that year, adding that the M32 had created a "concrete divide" between Eastville, St Paul's and Easton.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Local residents have complained about the noise on the M32.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] A report by the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs showed that traffic noise can be as loud as 75 decibels in neighbouring estates.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2014, a petition was created to campaign Bristol City Council to install quieter road surfaces and noise barriers along the motorway.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2011, a council gardening scheme created a horticultural landscape next to the southern end of the M32.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The project included planting of red poppies, cornflowers, and marigolds.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] A spokesman said they hoped it would enhance the view from the motorway and provide additional habitats for wildlife including bees and butterflies.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] The gardens were well received by locals and led to a city-wide project called Meadow Bristol, to grow similar meadows elsewhere.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] In 2021, the Government proposed reducing the speed limit where it is still 70 mph (110 km/h) to 60 mph (97 km/h) to reduce the quantity of nitrogen dioxide emissions along the road.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Data from driver location signs are used to provide distance and carriageway identification information.
[src:river-severn/a4032-road] Where a junction spans several hundred metres, both the start and end locations are given.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The **River Severn** (Welsh: *Afon Hafren*, pronounced [ˈavɔn ˈhavrɛn]) is the longest river in Great Britain, with a length of 220 miles (354 km).
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It is also the river with the most voluminous flow of water by far in all of England and Wales, with an average flow rate of 107 m3/s (3,800 cu ft/s) at Apperley, Gloucestershire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It rises in the Cambrian Mountains in mid Wales, at an altitude of 610 m (2,000 ft), on the Plynlimon massif, which lies close to the Ceredigion/Powys border near Llanidloes.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The river then flows through Shropshire, Worcestershire and Gloucestershire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The county towns of Shrewsbury, Worcester and Gloucester lie on its course.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Severn's major tributaries are the Vyrnwy, the Tern, the Teme, the Warwickshire Avon, and the Worcestershire Stour.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] By convention, the River Severn is usually considered to end, and the Severn Estuary to begin, after the Prince of Wales Bridge, between Severn Beach in South Gloucestershire and Sudbrook, Monmouthshire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The total area of the estuary's drainage basin is 4,409 square miles (11,419 km2).
[src:river-severn/river-severn] That figure excludes the area of the River Wye and the Bristol Avon, both of which flow into the Severn Estuary.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The estuary discharges into the Bristol Channel, which opens into the Celtic Sea and from there into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] An etymology has been proposed, which signifies that 'Severn' is an anglicised version of an ancient Celtic phrase signifying 'a gap (in the coastline)', referring to the estuary.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The name Severn is thought to derive from a British word *sabrinā*, possibly from an older form **samarosina*, meaning "land of summertime fallow".
[src:river-severn/river-severn] During the Roman occupation the *Severn* was known by the Romano-British Latin name *Sabrina*.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Welsh form of the name is **Afon Hafren** (pronounced [ˈavɔn ˈhavrɛn]) first recorded in the 12th-century *Historia Regum Britanniae*.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Old Welsh form of the name **Habren** was recorded c.800.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The English form of the name ("*Severn*") is derived from Old English *Sæfern*.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] However the name is also influenced by English dialect *seave* ("sedge, rush") hence the origin of the name *Seaverne* recorded in the 16th–17th century.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Common club-rush (*Schoenoplectus lacustris*) prefers to grow in shallow water such as that found in ponds, streams and river margins.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Hwicce people used the club-rush growing along the banks of the River Severn to make wicker baskets.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] In the Summer of 893 a coalition of all of the Danish armies in England made a determined attempt to annex western Mercia to Danish Mercia.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Old Norse *fara* – "to fare, to travel".
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Old Norse personal name *Sæfari* – "Seafarer".
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Old Norse name *Sæfari* ("Seafarer") lives on as the name of the Dalvík – Grímsey ferry in Iceland.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Severn's current form is the result of a multi-million year history and complex underlying geology, shaped in part by glaciation during the last ice age in the Pleistocene epoch of the Quaternary period.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Within Wales, the river runs through a landscape formed in Ordovician and Silurian rocks.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] As it enters the Shropshire Plain, these lower Palaeozoic rocks are replaced by Permian and Triassic age strata though largely unseen beneath a thick cover of Quaternary deposits.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Certain stretches also run across Carboniferous strata as at Shrewsbury and for much of the distance between Ironbridge and Bewdley.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Permo-Triassic bedrock then continues until the Severn moves intermittently onto the Jurassic outcrop from Tewkesbury southwards.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Only in the SSW-NNE aligned valley either side of Welshpool is there any obvious relationship to geological structure where the valley follows the lines of the Severn Valley Fault Belt.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] For much of the rest of its course it runs directly across geological structures.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It was first proposed in the 1900s that the former northerly course of the upper Severn was disrupted during the ice age by the blocking of its access to the Irish Sea through Cheshire, causing a large lake to develop across much of Shropshire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It was supposed that this lake, named as Lake Lapworth, overtopped its southern margin and rapidly cut down to form the Ironbridge Gorge providing the Severn with a southerly exit to the sea as remains the case today.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] An alternative theory which has gained favour in recent years does away with Lake Lapworth, suggesting that the upper Severn flowed beneath the icesheet in a bedrock hollow known as the Severn Trench eastwards from Melverley to the Ironbridge Gorge.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It is possible that the trench and gorge were cut over successive ice ages.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Over its length, there are a large number of tributaries, but the three largest feeding the non-tidal river are the Vyrnwy, the Teme and the Warwickshire Avon.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Wye, the Bristol Avon and the Usk all flow into the estuarine section of the Severn.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The main tributaries are described in sequence below.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The first tributary of significance is the Afon Dulas, joining from the south immediately upstream of Llanidloes, with the Afon Clywedog joining in the town.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Afon Cerist, bolstered by the Afon Trannon, and the Afon Carno join as left bank tributaries immediately upstream of Caersws.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Mochdre Brook enters on the western edge of Newtown, followed by the Bechan Brook just northeast of the town.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Mule enters at Abermule, and the River Rhiw east of Berriew, followed shortly by the Camlad which rises above Churchstoke and by the Luggy Brook.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The left bank Sylfaen Brook enters at Welshpool, and the Bele Brook via the New Cut east of Arddlin.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Vyrnwy, which begins at Lake Vyrnwy, flows eastwards through Powys, gathering the waters of the Banwy, Cain and Tanat, before forming part of the border between England and Wales, and joining the Severn near Melverley, Shropshire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Perry joins on the left bank above Shrewsbury, while both the Rad Brook and the Rea Brook, which flows northeast from its source at Marton Pool near the Welsh border, join the Severn within the town.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The left bank tributary, the River Tern, after flowing south from Market Drayton and being joined by the River Meese and the River Roden, meets the Severn at Attingham Park.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Worfe joins the Severn's left bank just above Bridgnorth, before the Mor, Borle and Dowles brooks join on the opposite bank over the next few miles, the last-named draining Wyre Forest.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Stour rises in the north of Worcestershire in the Clent Hills, near St Kenelm's Church at Romsley.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It flows north into the adjacent West Midlands at Halesowen.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It then flows westwards through Cradley Heath and Stourbridge, where it leaves the Black Country.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It is joined by the Smestow Brook at Prestwood before it winds around southwards to Kinver, and then flows back into Worcestershire.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It then passes through Wolverley, Kidderminster and Wilden to its confluence with the Severn at Stourport-on-Severn.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Dick Brook, Shrawley Brook and Grimley Brook enter on the right bank before the River Salwarpe, which runs through Droitwich enters on the opposite (east) bank.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Teme flows eastwards from its source in Mid Wales, straddling the border between Shropshire and Herefordshire; it is joined by the River Onny, River Corve and River Rea before it finally joins the Severn on the southern edge of Worcester.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Bushley Brook joins just upstream of the confluence of the Warwickshire Avon with the Severn at Tewkesbury.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] One of several Avons, this one flows west through Rugby, Warwick and Stratford-upon-Avon.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It is then joined by its tributary the River Arrow, before joining the Severn.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The rivers Swilgate and Chelt also join the Severn's left bank, as do the Hatherley and Horsbere brooks, before it reaches Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Leadon enters the tidal West Channel of the Severn at Over, immediately west of Gloucester.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Frome is the second significant tributary to enter the tidal stretch of the Severn, doing so at Framilode.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] Bideford Brook drains the easternmost part of the Forest of Dean, entering the Severn estuary east of Blakeney.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] On the opposite (southeast) bank the flow of the River Cam is usurped by the Gloucester and Sharpness Canal before reaching the estuary.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Lyd enters the west bank of the estuary at Lydney Harbour, opposite the place where Berkeley Pill carries the waters of the Little Avon River into it.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The final tributary before the Severn Bridge is the collection of streams which enter via Oldbury Pill.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The River Wye, from its source in Plynlimon in Wales (2 miles (3 km) from the source of the Severn), flows generally south east through the Welsh towns of Rhayader and Builth Wells.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] It enters Herefordshire, flows through Hereford, and is shortly afterwards joined by the River Lugg, before flowing through Ross-on-Wye and Monmouth, and then southwards where it forms part of the border between England (Forest of Dean) and Wales.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Wye flows into the Severn estuary south of the town of Chepstow.
[src:river-severn/river-severn] The Mounton Brook and Nedern Brooks enter on the Monmouthshire side between the two motorway crossings.
